<HEADLINE> SADC Free Trade Pact Still To be Finalised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Trade officials from the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) have yet to reach
agreement on details of a plan to liberalise trade among the
12-nation trading bloc, said a source here today.
</P>
<P>
The Free Trade Pact, approved by SADC heads of state in
Maseru, Lesotho, last August, envisaged the creation of an
eight-year free trade area in the region.
</P>
<P>
The protocol also called for a linkage between trade
liberalisation to region-wide industrial restructuring and
promotion of new investment as well as cooperation in trade
facilitation, promotion and rehabilitation of port facilities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the source quoted SADC spokesman Kgosi Moesi as saying
that only Mauritius had so far ratified the pact, more than five
months after political leaders gave their nod to the program.
</P>
<P>
However, Moesi indicated that a majority of members states were in
the process of ratifying the trade protocol, while some wanted to see
results of technical studies being done to establish which sectors and
product lines had to be covered by the free trade area.
</P>
<P>
He believed the delay was, in part, caused by the need of
governments to assess the sensitive sectors and to prioritise their
needs, but stressing that the political commitment to implement the
protocol was strong.
</P>
<P>
Last week, South Africa, which is currently chairing the SADC, gave
strong signals that it intended using the trade protocol to open its
markets faster to its SADC partners in a bid to rectify the long
running deficit the region had suffered in its trade with Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
The SADC comprises Angola, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mauritius,
Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa, Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and
Zimbabwe. enditem

