<HEADLINE> Clinton Imposes Ban on Federal Funds for Human Cloning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today imposed a ban on federal funds for any human cloning
experiments, saying the recent breakthrough in animal cloning
could raise troubling prospect.
</P>
<P>
"Today I am issuing a directive that bans the use of any
federal funds for any cloning of human beings. Effective
immediately, no federal agency may support, fund or undertake such
activity." Clinton stressed.
</P>
<P>
Because the privately funded scientists are not covered by the
directive, Clinton also asked for a voluntary moratorium on human
cloning experiments anywhere in the United States -- at least
until the legal and ethical issues can be sorted out by the whole
nation.
</P>
<P>
"I am urging the entire scientific and medical community, every
foundation, every university, every industry that supports work in
this area, to heed the federal government's example." Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
Last week President Clinton asked National Bioethics Advisory
Commission to conduct a thorough review of the legal and ethical
issues raised by the successful cloning of an adult sheep in
Scotland, and to recommend possible actions to prevent its abuse
and to report back to him in May.
</P>
<P>
Previously, Clinton approved a ban on federal funding for
research on human embryos, experiments which might hold promise
for the treatment of disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
