<HEADLINE> EU Trade Surplus Rises for Fourth Successive Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Union's trade
surplus with the rest of the world totalled 28.52 billion
U.S. dollars in the first three quarters of 1996, up slightly on
the 27.83 billion dollars recorded for the whole of 1995 and more
than three times the combined trade surpluses for 1993 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus was 7.13 billion dollars in 1994 and 1.38
billion dollars in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus in the third quarter of last year rose to an
estimated 16.56 billion dollars, compared with 1.38 billion
dollars in the first quarter and 10.58 billion dollars in the
second quarter, EU's statistical office Eurostat reported today.
</P>
<P>
The figures show that the EU's external trade has been in
surplus for 10 successive quarters.
</P>
<P>
Eurostat attributed the rise in the surplus to the 12.2 percent
growth of exports in the quarter over the same period of 1995.
</P>
<P>
In the third quarter of 1996, EU exports to the rest of the
world were 174.80 billion dollars while imports were 158.24
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Germany had the biggest surplus of 44.62 billion dollars in the
first nine months, followed by Italy, the Netherlands and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
At the opposite end of the scale, in the red, were the United
Kingdom with a deficit of 25.76 billion dollars, Greece, Spain,
Portugal and Austria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
