<HEADLINE> US New Home Sales Up Sharply in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- New home sales in the U.S.
increased to nearly an 11-year high in January because of
unseasonably warm weather in the Northeast and South.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Commerce Department reported today that sales of new,
single-family homes reached a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
870,000, the highest level since March 1986. It was a sharp
increase of 8.6 percent comparing with the sales in December.
</P>
<P>
The gain in new home sales was also propelled by relatively low
mortgage rates and moderate economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The increase followed advances of 0.5 percent in December and
12.9 percent in November. For all of 1996, 758,000 homes were sold
in U.S., the largest number since 1978.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, the sales increased by 63.4 percent in January, the
largest percentage gain since April 1993. Sales also jumped by
11.9 percent in the South. However, they fell 10.3 percent in the
Midwest and 5.9 percent in the West.
</P>
<P>
The strong sales overall reduced the inventory of completed but
unsold homes to a 4.5-month supply, down from 5 months in December
and 6.3 months a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Housing was one of the key sources of strength in the U.S.
economy last year. Analysts are expecting another good year for
housing but not quite as strong as last year.
</P>
<P>
Sales of existing homes in the U.S. have been strong as well.
The sales rose by 2.1 percent in January to a rate of 3.94
million, according to the National Association of Realtors last
week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
