<HEADLINE> Pakistan, Iran to Develop Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and Iran have stressed
the need to develop close fraternal ties and expand their
cooperation in all fields.
</P>
<P>
The need was expressed at a meeting here today between
Pakistan's Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan and the visiting
Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister Morteza Sarmadi.
</P>
<P>
Sarmadi, who is here as the special envoy of the Iranian
government, called on Ayub Khan and discussed with him matters of
mutual interest.
</P>
<P>
According to informed sources, the two sides also discussed the
security measures taken after the attack last month on the Iranian
Cultural Center in the central Pakistani city of Multan.
</P>
<P>
An Iranian official from the cultural center and six other
Pakistanis were killed in the Multan incident.
</P>
<P>
The two sides expressed their abhorrence at terrorism and
underlined their determination not to allow such incidents to
derail the bilateral relationship.  
</P>
