<HEADLINE> Hun Sen: CPP to Continue Cooperation With Funcinpec </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Second Prime Minister
Hun Sen said here today that his Cambodian People's Party (CPP)
will act with the cooperation pact with the Funcinpec Party.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen, who also serves as vice chairman of the CPP, said that
he did not read the monthly bulletin in which King Norodom
Sihanouk expressed his intention to abdicate his throne, noting
the king is the head of state for ever according to the current
constitution.
</P>
<P>
The second prime minister made the remarks today at the signing
ceremony for officially forming a political alliance between the
CPP and the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen said the relations between the CPP and the Funcinpec
will be put to track as defined in the 1991 pact between the two
parties.
</P>
<P>
The two parties became partners in the coalition of the Royal
Government following the 1993 national elections. But the
relations between them became tense in the past months, climaxing
at bloodshed clashes in Battambang province last month between
soldiers loyal to the two parties.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen confirmed that at the High Command meeting last week,
First Prime Minister Norodom Ranariddh and himself,
co-commanders-in-chief of the armed forces, agreed to give
additional mandate to a eight-member committee solving the
partisan armed conflicts in Battambang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
