<HEADLINE> Majority Verdict to be Accepted in "Match-fix" Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- A majority verdict will be take in
the the trial of three football stars accused of match-fixing,
the judge told the jury on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The jury of eight men and three women immediately retired again
to continue their deliberations.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the jury watched again video footage they saw during
the trial as they tried to reach verdicts on the 34th day of the
trial at Winchester Crown Court in England.
</P>
<P>
The video shows Grobbelaar accepting 2,000 pounds (about 3,200
U.S. dollars) from Vincent in the belief that the cash has come
from a match-fixing syndicate.
</P>
<P>
The jury retired on Monday at the end of the seventh week of
the trial to consider verdicts against former Liverpool and
Southampton star Grobbelaar, 39, ex-Aston Villa and Wimbledon
striker John Fashanu, 34, the former Wimbledon keeper Hans Segers,
35, and Malaysian businessman Heng Suan Lim, 31.
</P>
<P>
The defendants all deny conspiring to give and accept corrupt
payments to influence, or attempt to influence, the outcome of
football matches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
