<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Leading Index Rises 0.3 Percent in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 4 (Xinhua) -- A key index of future economic
activity in the U.S. rose 0.3 percent in January, another sign of
economic growth amid heightened concerns that the Federal Reserve
may soon raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The gain in the Index of Leading Economic Indicators, released
today by the New York based Conference Board, follows a 0.1
percent rise in December and a revised 0.1 percent increase in
November. Wall Street had been expecting a similar gain in
January.
</P>
<P>
The leading index itself is designed to forecast economic
activity six to nine months in advance. Thus, its January gain
suggests the economy will continue to expand at least through the
Summer.
</P>
<P>
Other recent economic news supports that belief.
</P>
<P>
Of its 10 components of the index, six rose for the month. The
biggest help came from rising manufacturers' orders for consumer
goods and falling weekly unemployment claims. Components hurting
the index most were retail vendor performance and the average
factory workweek.
</P>
<P>
The index's January reading of 103.0 compares with a revised
102.7 in December and a revised November level of 102.6. The index
operates from a base of 100, set in 1987.  
</P>
