<HEADLINE> Nambia Promotes Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Nambia has launched a
community-based tourism project in a bid to benefit all
Namibians, the Southern African Broadcasting Association (SABA)
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Namibian Minister of Tourism and Environment Gert Hanekom
described the Damaraland Camp Project as a significant step
toward the country's socio-economic development.
</P>
<P>
The scheme, located on the Huab River in northwestern Namibia,
is a joint venture between the privately-owned Wilderness Safaris
and the Bergsig-De-Riet people.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement on the joint venture, the camp and its
assets will ultimately be the property of the Bergsig-De Riet
people, one of Namibia's poor minorities, living alongside the
Huab River.
</P>
<P>
The community-private sector project is designed to raise
national income, increase employment in the formal and informal
sectors, reduce income disparities between the rich and the poor,
and alleviate poverty, Hanekom said.
</P>
<P>
More than 200,000 U.S. Dollars have been allocated to the
project, which will benefit 11 communities along the Huab River,
SABA said. enditem

