<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Direct Talks in Cyprus Expected Soon, UN Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations hopes that
direct negotiations between Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash will be in the cards in
the first half of 1997, a U.N. official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Gustave Feissel, resident representative for Cyprus of
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, was telling reporters after an
hour-long meeting with Clerides at the Presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
He said "our objective is to get the two leaders together
soon, and everybody is talking about the first half of 1997 and
hopefully that will be the case."
</P>
<P>
Feissel said he briefed the Cypriot president on his recent
discussions in New York with the U.N. chief and reiterated U.N.
determination to move things forward so that the two leaders can
meet as soon as possible in the middle of this year.
</P>
<P>
"We are working very hard to make such a meeting possible,"
he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the talks could take place in Cyprus, Feissel said
"that remains to be seen, but obviously there are advantages in
doing it elsewhere."
</P>
<P>
However, the U.N. representative said the venue for the talks
was not discussed with Clerides.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Kofi Annan sent letters to Clerides and Denktash,
Greece and Turkey in which he expressed his determination to move
things forward.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of an
Athens-backed coup.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community have intensified their
efforts since this year to try to bring an early solution to the
protracted Cyprus problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
