<HEADLINE> Arafat Pledges to Continue Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat said on Tuesday his People will carry on with the peace
process in the Middle East in spite of all difficulties made by
the Israel's current Likud government on their road toward the
goal set by him and late Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
"We have no other alternative. And in spite all of the
difficulties, which we are taking, we have one alternative, to
carry on with the peace process," Arafat told reporters at a news
conference at the National Press Club in Washington D.C..
</P>
<P>
"That is our strategic target, and we are insisting to carry on
with it," he repeated his emphasis on his continued job in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government approved a plan last Wednesday to
establish 6,500 Jewish homes in Abu Ghenaim, east Jerusalem, which
was captured by Israel during the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli decision on housing project has drawn world wide
criticism and U.S. President Bill Clinton accused Israel of
building "mistrust" on Monday when he met visiting Arafat at the
White House for talks over the controversial Israeli housing plan.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said he had a "very constructive, positive, warm talks"
with Clinton, who gave the Palestinians the support by denouncing
Israel's decision on the Jewish settlement in east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"I can't say and I haven't the right to say what he (Clinton)
is going to do, but I am sure he will push forward with all his
capability, with all his capacity, to save the peace process," the
Palestinian leader said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat stressed that Israel's decision to establish new Jewish
homes in east Jerusalem was violating an agreement between him and
Rabin, which stipulates that no demographic change to be done
during the transitional period, including settlements, including
the situation of Jerusalem....
</P>
<P>
"The last decision to build a new settlement in Abu Ghehaim
Mountain is a real challenge to the peace process because it
will isolate Jerusalem more and more and more and more, and to
separate between Jerusalem and Bethlehem," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
