<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Fed Chairman Says Inflation Overstated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed)
Chairman Alan Greenspan said today that inflation in the U.S. is
overstated and renewed his call to fix the inflation gauge.
</P>
<P>
Testifying before the Budget Committee of the U.S. House of
Representatives, Greenspan said, "The best available evidence
suggests that there is almost a 100 percent probability that we
are overcompensating the average Social Security recipient for
increases in the cost of living."
</P>
<P>
He said that because the CPI is also used to adjust individual
income taxes, the upward bias also means that there is a "100
percent probability that we are causing the inflation-adjusted
burden of the income tax system to decline more rapidly than I
presume Congress intends."
</P>
<P>
The Fed Chairman suggested the U.S. Congress adopt a two-track
approach to revise the Consumer Price Index (CPI) so that it will
provide a better yardstick for adjusting benefits and the income
tax system to compensate for inflation.
</P>
<P>
A five-member Congressional advisory commission headed by
Stanford economist Michael Boskin has said the current CPI
overstated the U.S. inflation by 1.1 percentage points annually.
</P>
<P>
The panel said if this bias is not corrected it will cost the
government 1 trillion dollars in overly generous pension payments
and incorrect adjustments to tax returns over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
Supporting the conclusions, Greenspan said there was a "very
high probability" that the exaggeration in the CPI ranges between
0.5 percentage point and 1.5 percentage points per year.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan's suggestion for an independent group of experts
received support in the past week from both Republicans in the
U.S. Senate and the White House.
</P>
<P>
However, the American Association of Retired Persons argues
that any changes affecting the CPI should be made only by the
experts at the Bureau of Labor Statistics, the agency that
produces the inflation gauge.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 million Americans are receiving Social Security
and other government benefits and their benefits will be reduced
if the inflation gauge is revised down. Enitem


nnnn
01:09 01:09 g # NAB
</P>
</TEXT>
