<HEADLINE> Tourism Starts Recovering in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 4 (Xinhua) -- After the conclusion of the
Hebron Agreement between Israel and the Palestinians in January,
signs are pointing to a recovery of the tourism in this country,
Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Avraham Rosental, director-general of the
Israeli Hotel Association, as saying that reservations in local
hotels have been up since the implementation of the Hebron
Agreement.
</P>
<P>
Rosental said that after six months of decline in the number of
tourists coming to Israel, tourist operators are suggesting that
the recovery they have been waiting for has finally started.
</P>
<P>
After a series of suicide bombing attacks in February and March
last year, and later a serious armed confrontation between Israeli
soldiers and Palestinian police in September, which left dozens of
death respectively, Israel's tourism industry had suffered a huge
set back in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Rosental said that the Israeli government and private tourist
operators, as well as the Hotel Association, are carrying out
market promotions in Europe and the United States to attract
tourists.
</P>
<P>
Rosental stressed the importance of the continuation of Middle
East peace process in helping further develop the tourism industry
in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that Israel and together with the whole Middle
East is a very attractive market for visitors, but, "only a
right peaceful environment will bring more tourists to an
area." 
</P>
