<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No BSE Risk from Cows Milk: EU Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- EU scientists said in a report
issued today that there is no risk of transmission of the
BSE(Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy) disease from cows' milk.
</P>
<P>
"The report concludes that bovine milk from clinically healthy
cows and products made from it can be safely consumed," European
Commission agriculture spokesman Gerard Kiely told a press
briefing.
</P>
<P>
The EU's scientific Veterinary Committee nonetheless said in
the report that current controls which prohibit the consumption of
milk from clinically suspect cattle should be maintained.
</P>
<P>
The Committee also concluded that the controls should be
extended to include colostrum from cattle suspected to have BSE.
Colostrum is secreted from cows to feed calves after giving birth.
</P>
<P>
But it added that exceptions can be made for colostrum or milk
from such cattle used to feed the cow's own calf.
</P>
<P>
The EU scientific committee had been examining the interim
results of a British study that suggested that cows could transmit
BSE to their calves.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission said in August 1996 that pending
further scientific research that there was no scientific evidence
that milk carries BSE or mad cow disease.
</P>
<P>
The EU imposed a worldwide ban in March 1996 on all exports of
British beef and derived products in order to protect public
health.
</P>
<P>
The ban followed a British government admission of a probable
link between BSE and a deadly human equivalent Creutzfeldt-Jakob
Disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
