<HEADLINE> Food Security Threatened in SADC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Recent political and economic
changes in the Southern African Development Community (SADC) have
weakened the region's original aim of having a sound food
security policy, a SADC official claimed here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing delegates to a three-day conference on new food
strategies, SADC Deputy Executive Secretary Lengolo Monyane said
the change in regional governments' approaches to economic
management meant that the objective of food security could no
longer be achieved as was originally anticipated.
</P>
<P>
If improvements in food security were to be realised, he said,
there should be broad participation of all stakeholders in the
reduction of malnutrition in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said given the new economic and political setting in which
it was now operating, SADC as an economic grouping was now facing
enormous challenges.
</P>
<P>
He said some countries in SADC had a great potential for
agriculture, but required investment in infrastructure to realise
this asset.
</P>
<P>
The conference, which ends on Thursday, is part of a process
to appraise the functions of the SADC food, agriculture and
natural resources sub-sector and see how it can contribute to
food security in the region.
</P>
<P>
European Union representative to Zimbabwe Michael Laidler
stressed southern African countries should start thinking new
ways of ensuring permanent food security in a region prone to
recurrent droughts.
</P>
<P>
He said a regional food security financing facility should be
arranged.
</P>
<P>
He added the EU was funding a six million US Dollars regional
food security training project aimed at building up the regional
training capacity by strengthening existing training
institutions. enditem

