<HEADLINE> Central African Sub-Regional Meeting Opens in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, March 4 (Xinhua) -- A sub-regional meeting of the
central african states of the African, Caribbean and Cacific
countries (ACP) was opened here today.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Camerounian Prime Minister Peter
Mafani Musonge
called on the Euruopean Union (EU) to help the ACP countries
integrate economies and avoid further marginalization.
</P>
<P>
On his part, ACP Secretary General Ng'andu Peter Magande
called for genuine dialogue between the ACP and the EU. He said
Africa cannot be spectator on the international scene in the face
of world competition and globalization.
</P>
<P>
Economy and finance ministers of the 8 central African states
are attending the meeting. Others present at the meeting were
representatives of the European Commission and the general secretary
of the Economic and Customs Union of the Central African States.
</P>
<P>
The four-day sub-regional meeting is aimed at examining the
ACP-EU relations.
</P>
<P>
The relations between the ACP and EU can be traced
to the Lome Convention signed in 1975. Since then, assistance in
development offered by EU to the ACP countries has lasted for 22
years. It has been consistent in two major areas: technical and
financial.
</P>
<P>
In Cameroun, financial assistance has contributed tremendously
in ameliorating the living conditions of many citizens. enditem

