<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relative Calm Returns to South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Following a week of tension, a
relative calm returned to south Lebanon today except sporadic
shellings by Israeli forces at suspected guerrillas targets.
</P>
<P>
Security sources reported several 155mm artillery shells fired
by the Israeli occupation forces in the Israeli self-proclaimed
"security zone" hitting vicinities of the south Lebanese market
town of Nabatiyeh without causing casualties.
</P>
<P>
Israeli warplanes hovered at low altitude over Western Beqaa
in southeast Lebanon over the night and during the daytime.
</P>
<P>
Israeli helicopters also carried out reconnaissance flights
over the area of Sour in the western sector of south Lebanon,
according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
In a relative development, a five-nation committee monitoring
a limited truce on the Lebanese-Israeli border called today on
all the fighting parties in south Lebanon to comply with a
cease-fire understanding which Lebanon and Israel reached in
April, 1996.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire monitoring committee comprising representatives
of France, Israel, Lebanon, Syria and the United States ended a
20-hour meeting at the south Lebanese border town of Naqoura this
morning.
</P>
<P>
Delegates of the five countries held the meeting in the
headquarters of the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) to
discuss an Israeli complaint over an alleged breach of the
ceasefire understanding by the Lebanese resistance fighters last
week.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued at the end of the meeting, the monitoring
group "unanimously reiterates the necessity that all the fighters
should completely comply with the April understanding (1996) which
barres attacks from and on civilian areas."
</P>
<P>
"The group demands all the parties to avoid directly or
indirectly using ways of military operations which could expose
civilians to risks, and it calls for an observance of
self-restraint," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese foreign ministry sources said that during the
meeting, the Lebanese delegation rejected the Israeli claims that
the resistance had violated the April truce by mounting an attack
from a civilian area last Friday.
</P>
<P>
One Israeli soldier was killed and three others were wounded in
the Ambush inside the Israeli buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
that the Lebanese team presented photographs of damage the Israeli
retribution caused in a string of village facing the occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
Seven Lebanese civilians have been killed in Israeli
bombardment in south Lebanon since the end of a 17-day Israeli
blitz in south Lebanon last April, in which some 200 Lebanese,
mainly civilians, were killed.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the 1,100-square-kilometer "security zone" in
1985 in a bid to protect northern Israel from cross-border
attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
