<HEADLINE> OAU Welcomes Ban on Anti-Personnel Landmines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Secretary General of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) today welcomed the recent
decisions of the South African and Mozambican governments to ban
anti-personnel landmines.
</P>
<P>
A press release from the OAU said the South African government
on February 19 decided to ban the use, development, production and
stockpiling of anti-personnel landmines with immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
The government of Mozambique on February 25
also decided with immediate effect to prohibit in its territory the
production of, trade in as well as the use and non-authorized
transportation of anti-personnel landmines, the release added.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that the secretary general stressed the value of
these exemplary decisions of the two governments, which are fully in
accordance with a number of OAU resolutions on this issue and
strengthens the momentum generated by the Ottawa Conference held
in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
''Only such decisive acts by states and other
organizations can put an end to the terrible consequences caused
by the generalized and indiscriminats use of landmines,'' the release
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The secretary general, however, deplored the severe negative
long-term impact which the use of anti-personnel landmines had on
the social, economic and environmental circumstances of millions of
Africans and their countries long after the end of the conflicts in
which these weapons were deployed, the release said.
</P>
<P>
The secretary general also appealed to the international
community to increase its assistance to the affected countries of
Africa in their attempts to rid themselves of this plague, according
to the release. enditem

