<HEADLINE> German President Warns Against Racism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, March 4 (Xinhua) -- President Roman Herzog of Germany
warned here today against all forms of racism and xenophobia, and
called for more tolerance in society.
</P>
<P>
In a speech delivered to mark of the European Year against
Racism, Herzog said it was Germany which shoulders the special
historical responsibility to fight against racism and xenophobia.
And It should also stand ready to take such a responsibility in
the future.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that foreigners in Germany should not only be
seen as social welfare recipients, they have also made
considerable contributions to the economic success of the country.
</P>
<P>
The European Year against Racism was declared by the Council of
the European Union (EU). Each EU member state has its own events
to persuade the public against the evils of racism throughout the
year.
</P>
<P>
Opening the German events in Berlin today, Herzog also called
on citizens to be alert even to the way they use words.
</P>
<P>
"If someone says 'the Jews', 'the Poles' or 'the employers',
watch out!" he said, adding that it was not enough just to be
disgusted at racism or to punish racist acts. "Bridges have to be
built between different cultures," Herzog said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
