<HEADLINE> Zairean FM Calls on UN to Make Peace Plan "Operational" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Zairean Foreign Minister Gerard
Kamanda Wa Kamanda today asked France and the United Nations to
take necessary measures to make a U.N. five-point peace plan for
Zaire "operational."
</P>
<P>
Kamanda, who is on a visit here, said in a declaration to the
press that Zairean rebels led by Laurent-Desire Kabila have
"categorically rejected all ceasing of hostilities."
</P>
<P>
He asked the United Nations Security Council to "enact
practical ways of control over the withdrawal and disarmament of
foreign troops, including mercenaries and militias, from Zairean
territory."
</P>
<P>
The French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said
today that it is essential for all Zairean parties to "show
without ambiguity their adhesion to the five-point peace plan of
the United Nations."
</P>
<P>
He also said that "the continuation of fightings (in Zaire)
should be firmly discouraged by all those who can exercise their
influence in the region," and that France "asks its partners to
exert all the possible pressures to that end."
</P>
<P>
The United States Monday indirectly called on Zairean rebels to
stop their military actions, saying that "the pursuit of
fightings risks to harm" the mediation effort being launched by
the United Nations, the European Union, the United States and
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The five-point peace plan, written by U.N. special envoy for
the Great Lakes region Mohamed Sahnoun, calls for an immediate
ending of hostilities, the withdrawal of foreign forces from
Zaire, respect of national territorial integrity, protection of
refugees, and a solution for the crisis through dialogue. 
</P>
