<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People in UK Told to Boil Water in Parasite Scare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 4 (Xinhua) - Tap water in England is increasingly
threatened with contamination by parasite which causes sickness as
water companies try to maintain supplies after two years of
drought, experts warn.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of families have been told to boil their water before
using it after a warning that they risk sickness and severe
diarrhoea.
</P>
<P>
The advice was issued by public health officials after 32
people became unwell due to a water-borne micro-organism,
cryptosporidium, which causes serious and prolonged stomach upset.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Three Valleys Water said it did not know how
the parasite, cryptosporidium had entered its water.
</P>
<P>
The decision to issue an instruction to boil water was taken
after an emergency meeting of public health officials with the
water company on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
More cases were confirmed soon after 300,000 notices had been
delivered advising people not to use unboiled tap water "until
further notice".
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Brent and Harrow said that of 12 confirmed
cases, 10 were children. West Hertfordshire health authority said
it had had three times the usual level of cases.
</P>
<P>
The parasite cryptosporidium is resistant to most
disinfectants, including bleach and water companies' chief
treatment is filtration.
</P>
<P>
The organism reproduces inside the gut and can be passed
easily from person to person, experts warn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
