<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Rejects International Pressure on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu today brushed aside increasing international
pressure on Israel's decision to build a settlement in eastern
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after meeting with visiting French Foreign Minister
Herve de Charette, Netanyahu said Israel was determined to go
ahead with the controversial building plan in Har Homa in
southeastern Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, the Israeli leader announced the delay of the
construction work for a few days due to technical and legal
reasons. He denied that this was connected to his upcoming visit
to Egypt Wednesday, during which the Har Homa issue is expected
to top the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu rejected the mounting international pressure on him
to revoke the building plan. He said that, if not for technical
difficulties, Israel would begin surveys in Har Homa today. He
added that the surveys would be conducted in a few days and
bulldozers would be sent to break the ground within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
According to the Har Homa plan, Israel will build 2,500 of the
total 6,500 housing units in the first stage of the project
within three years.
</P>
<P>
On the further Israeli troop pullouts on West Bank which
should be completed by Friday under the Hebron agreement,
Netanyahu promised that the first stage of the three-phase
redeployments would be carried out immediately after the cabinet
made a decision Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Israel Television Channel I quoted Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai as saying that the pullouts could be completed within
14 hours after the cabinet decision. Israel is expected to hand
over 6 to 10 percent of the West Bank now under its control to
the Palestinian National Authority.
</P>
<P>
De Charette today also held talks with his Israeli
counterpart David Levy, during which they agreed to set up a
committee under their direct supervision to seek ways to improve
relations in areas of politics, economy, and culture.
</P>
<P>
The French foreign minister's three-day trip here is aimed at
mending ties soured by the stormy visit last October by French
President Jacques Chirac, who angered many Israelis by clashing
with Israeli guards during a tour to the Jerusalem's Old
City. Despite Israel's opposition, Chirac also urged it to
accept the concept of a Palestinian state, which he said would be
the only way to bring security to Israel.
</P>
<P>
France, which maintains traditional strong ties with Middle
Eastern Arab countries, has been trying hard to play a greater
role in the Israeli-Arab peace process to break the monopoly by
the United States. But Israel has rejected this demand, citing
what it called France's pro-Arab stance.
</P>
<P>
De Charette today deliberately denied that his country was
taking a pro-Arab stance, saying Paris had an open heart for
many friends. Perhaps in a good-will gesture to Israel, de
Charette avoided this time visiting the Orient House, the PNA's
de facto representative office in eastern Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
