<HEADLINE> Cyprus Launches Cancer Control Program for Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has launched a program on
control of women's breast and cervix cancer, which will begin on
March 18 in the capital of Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the program at a press conference here today, Health
Minister Manolis Christofides said that a total of 1,800 new
cases of cancer were officially recorded in Cyprus in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The minister said skin cancer ranked the first with 522
cases, followed by breast cancer, urinary bladder ones, stomach
cancer, cervix cancer, bronchus and lung and ovarian cancer.
</P>
<P>
Christofides said that the program will cover some 2,000
women aged between 25 and 65 from the Nicosia greater area, who
will undergo the PAP SMEAR (Papanicolaou smear test for early
detection of cervix cancer) test and a mammography at the Nicosia
General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the minister added, efforts to introduce
the program in all hospitals will be intensified in order to
cover all women living in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is for every Cypriot woman to undergo an examination
every other year," Christofides stressed.
</P>
<P>
Christofides said check-ups in remote rural areas will be
carried out by a mobile unit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
