<HEADLINE> Paris Club, Nigeria Differ on Debt Figure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Paris Club of creditors is
pressing Nigeria to pay up its external debt, which according to
it, now amounts to 48 billion U.S. Dollars, instead of the 28
billion Dollars as claimed by Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The "Vanguard", a major Nigerian newspaper reported today that
the total debt is broken into 32.58 billion Dollars as capital,
and another 16 billion in unpaid arrears plus interest, according
to the Paris Club.
</P>
<P>
Also according to the club, Nigeria now owes 21.67 billion
Dollars to it, 4.41 billion to multilateral creditors, 3.15
billion in promissory notes, 2.05 billion to London Club and 1.31
billion in non-Paris bilateral debts, all excluding arrears and
interest.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's Finance Minister Anthony Ani announced in his 1997
budget breakdown that his country owes a total of 28.06 billion
Dollars to external creditors by the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
This includes 16.94 billion Dollars in arrears and 11.12
billion in interest, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, excluding penalties, Nigeria owes a
total of 19.09 billion Dollars to the 17 members of the Paris
Club as at November 30, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has paid more than 10 billion Dollars in payments to
private creditors in Europe in the last five years, the newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
To prevent its debt from further increasing, Nigeria has
stopped borrowing from the World Bank in 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-04 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Slams at Israeli Settlement Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 4 (Xinhua) -- On the eve of Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu's visit to Cairo, Egypt today criticized the
Jewish state's settlement practices, the Egyptian MENA news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Foreign Minister for Legal Affairs and International
Agreements Hussein Hassouna said Israel's policy of Judaization
and settlement in the occupied East Jerusalem is a violation of
international law and U.N. Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
On the Israeli government's insistence on building Jewish homes
in East Jerusalem, the Egyptian senior official said that the Arab
stand on occupied Palestinian lands is based on legal principles.
</P>
<P>
He spoke of U.N. resolutions 242 and 338 and other U.N. terms
banning the seizure of land by force, adding that any change in
the demographic structure of Jerusalem is illegal.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mofid Shihab, chairman of the Shura Council
(consultative conference) Committee of Arab and Foreign Affairs
and National Security denounced the Israeli settlement plan as a
frank violation of Oslo agreements.
</P>
<P>
"Jerusalem and settlements issues top the list of final phase
negotiations, and none of the two parties (of Israel and
Palestine) is allowed to unilaterally undertake measures that
might affect those negotiations," Shihab said.
</P>
<P>
He said the decision reveals Israel's attempt to impose fait
accompli on the lands it has occupied prior to the negotiations,
to hinder the negotiating process and to pressure the
Palestinians and to determine results of negotiations in advance.
</P>
<P>
Shihab called upon the United States, co-sponsor of the peace
process, to take necessary measures to halt Israeli practices
which will obstruct the peace march.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's visit here Wednesday comes exactly a week after
Israel decided to build 6,500 housing units for Jewish settlers
in Har Homa (Gabal Abu Ghoneim), a tree-covered hill in East
Jerusalem seized by Israel from Jordan in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
Arabs regard it as an Israeli attempt to tighten grip on
Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want to have as the capital of
their future state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
