<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Expert Commends Tanzania's Efforts in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 4 (Xinhua) -- An American expert today
commended Tanzania's efforts in fighting graft and called for
strengthening of the Prevention of Corruption Bureau by providing
it with adequate working tools and well trained staff.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here today, Deputy Commissioner
of Investigations at the city of New York, USA, Kevin Ford, said
that he was highly impressed with the government's efforts in the
on-going anti-corruption drive in the country.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that more efforts should be made to mobilize
the people to take part in the campaign. He also said that the
Prevention of Corruption Bureau must be strengthened to enable it
to cope with modern criminals using sophisticated tricks.
</P>
<P>
The American expert, who is on a two-week tour of Tanzania,
said he had met several government officials at the Prevention
of Corruption Bureau and the Leadership Ethics Commission, where
he shared with them ideas and experiences in fighting corruption.
</P>
<P>
Ford said that he was of the opinion that low wages in the
civil service, bureaucracy and existence of complicated
regulatory mechanism are among factors that fan corruption.
</P>
<P>
He held that revision of salary structures so as to provide
wages that will enable people to afford essential living expenses
is effective in controlling petty corruption.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the American expert said grand corruption could be
curbed by having a transparent system, where procedures for
awarding contracts and tenders should be known.
</P>
<P>
He, therefore, called for a campaign that will make all
countries pass legislation against foreign corrupt practices. He
said in some countries firms are allowed to bribe foreign
governments while in pursuit of contracts.
</P>
<P>
"Some governments waive tax for expenses incurred on bribery
abroad," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The American expert had some reservations of the leadership
ethics law, saying that much as disclosure of assets is a step in
the right direction in prevention of corruption at public
offices, more transparency is still desirable.
</P>
<P>
He said the public should have access to that information when
there is need.
</P>
<P>
Ford also called for closer co-operation between the
Prevention of Corruption Bureau, the Directorate of Criminal
Investigations and the Attorney General's Chambers in handling
cases.
</P>
<P>
The American expert said at the city of New York, prosecutors
work very closely with detectives and investigation officials, a
factor that has contributed to 90 percent success to all
prosecutions done. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
