<HEADLINE> UN Team Accuses UNITA Radio of False Reporting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Angola
Verification Mission today issued a communique, accusing the
UNITA of unfounded reporting by its radio.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that the UNITA controlled radio has
released a series of untrue reports recently, saying that it is
not helpful to the peace process in Angola.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time the UN inspection team has criticized
the UNITA's radio for its unfounded reports.
</P>
<P>
In the communique, the UN mission urged the staff of the radio
to have a good knowledge of resolutions approved by the UN
Security Council and the Joint Commission of the Angolan Peace
Process in order to issue true reports and promote national
reconciliation in the country.
</P>
<P>
On February 28, the UNITA radio reported that Deputy Commander
of the UN peacekeeping troops based in Angola General Saksena
inspected central Angola city Andulo for having a grasp of the
military situation in that area.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that the government troops had occupied
some areas near Andulo and were ready to capture the city, adding
that the news had been confirmed by the deputy commander.
</P>
<P>
But the communique noted that the aim of Saksena's inspection
was to resolve the contradictions between local UNITA leaders and
UN peacekeepers there.
</P>
<P>
It also declared that the report was totally unfounded and
Saksena had never confirmed this news and did not mention the
matter at all when meeting UNITA leaders.
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, the UNITA radio also issued
distorted report on the Angolan peace process yesterday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
