<HEADLINE> Jewish Organization Considers Suing Le Pen Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The world's oldest international
Jewish organization B'nai Brith is considering suing the president
of the French far-right National Front (FN) party, Jean-Marie Le
Pen, over defamation.
</P>
<P>
Le Pen claimed in an interview in a newly published book that
French President Jacques Chirac was "taken hostage" by B'nai Brith
and other Jewish organizations by agreeing to lose in the 1988
presidential election "in exchange for enormous sums of money and
exceptional international support."
</P>
<P>
The Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted Tommy Baer, president of
the U.S.-based Jewish organization, as saying in Jerusalem that
his organization is now looking into the laws of France to see if
the declarations of Le Pen make up a defamation against B'nai
Brith.
</P>
<P>
In the book "The Novel of a President," a biography of Chirac
written by journalists Nicolas Domenach and Maurice Szafran, Le
Pen said that Chirac also had promised B'nai Brith that his
gaullist RPR party would never ally with the FN, even though it
needed the latter to form a majority.
</P>
<P>
Baer told AFP that B'nai Brith is "formally non-political" and
"has specific relations neither with Chirac, nor with any other
man of politics, no matter where he is."
</P>
<P>
Calling the remarks by Le Pen as "scandalously and classically
anti-Semitic," Baer said that B'nai Brith will tell France and
French people that the FN is a danger not only for Jews, but also
for all French people.
</P>
<P>
He said that FN does not "incarnate the better part in the
French tradition but represents the return to the time of
fascism."
</P>
<P>
"It is time that the French people reject Le Pen and realize
that he is a dangerous mishigge (meaning fool in Yiddish)," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
