<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey's Islamist-Led Coalition Survives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's coalition government led
by pro-Islamic Welfare Party (RP) Chairman Necmettin Erbakan this
evening survived a no-confidence vote in the face of a military
challenge which has strained the unity of the alliance.
</P>
<P>
The government won the vote 272 to 265 in the 550-seat
legislative. The motion was filed to censure the government for
granting high-rate pay hikes to army personnel and police
forces while ignoring other branches of the civil servants.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan's coalition has faced mounting pressure after a
warning from the military about increasing "fundamentalist"
activities and signs of discontent from the conservative wing of
the alliance led by Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister
Tansu Ciller.
</P>
<P>
Addressing his RP deputies, Erbakan said: "Parliament gives
the job of serving the nation to the government and the
government is responsible only to parliament."
</P>
<P>
Erbakan made clear he would disregard most of the commitments
the military wanted him to sign. He played down the deep
division which cast doubt on the strength of Turkey's democracy
and the chances of survival for the troubled coalition.
</P>
<P>
The National Security Council Friday presented Erbakan with
an ultimatum, demanding him to agree to a 22-point code of
conduct.
</P>
<P>
These included a return to ban on conspicuously traditional
Muslim garb, the limitation of clerical education, a
reintroduced ban on religion-based political parties, the
outlawing of recently-prolific Muslim sects and orders which
assail secular laws adopted from the West.
</P>
<P>
The government cleared another hurdle later today when the
parliament voted 274 to 258 against launching an inquiry into
Justice Minister Sevket Kazan, a main aide of Erbkan, over his
"anti-secular" activities.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with Turkish President Suleymen Demirel,
Ciller said the coalition government would go on.
</P>
<P>
She dismissed accusations that the RP-led coalition government
had violated the state's constitutional secularism and her True
Path Party's (DYP) presence in the coalition was an insurance
for secularism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
