<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: German Nuclear Waste Convoy on Its Last Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Against all resistance from
anti-nuclear protesters, a convoy of six lorries carring nuclear
waste from Germany and France today finally started on its final
stage of the journey to the storage depot at northern German town
of Gorleben, about six hours behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
The controversial shipment of nuclear waste from two German
power plants and a reprocessing plant in France, first began its
journey on railway from southwestern Germany last Friday,
accompanied by tens of thousands of anti-nuclear protesters and
guarded by 30,000 police officers in postwar Germany's biggest
security operation.
</P>
<P>
On Monday the altogether six containers of nuclear waste,
weighing 750 tons, arrived at the northern German town of
Dannenberg where they were reloaded onto trucks.
</P>
<P>
At 11:40 a.m. Wednesday, the nuclear waste convoy along with
police vehicles left the heavily-guarded Dannenberg railway
station for the final, snail's-pace stage of their journey to the
storage facilities at Gorleben, some 20 kilometers away in the
east.
</P>
<P>
About 10 kilometers from Dannenberg, at the village of
Quickborn, militant protesters were earlier in skirmishes with
police. Petrol bombs were thrown. Police later also discovered and
defused a home-made bomb along the road to be possibly used by
the convoy.
</P>
<P>
Overnight, several thousands of demonstrators trying to block
the shipment staged peaceful sit-in near the exit road at the
Dannenberg railway station. But they were forcibly dispersed
Wednesday morning by police using water cannons. More than 100
people were injured in the operations, and 38 people were
temporarily detained.
</P>
<P>
One bank employee was quoted by the media as saying after the
dispersal that "This is a power play. This is about principles.
The government has decided to act and it wants to have its way,
regardless of what people say."
</P>
<P>
Another demonstrator who was in a similar protest last year
said the police were having more difficulty this time because the
protest was better organized than last year and also have more
support from the locals.
</P>
<P>
The anti-nuclear protest has grown in volume every year since
the transport of nuclear waste to Gorleben started three years
ago. One critic described the event as "an annual nuclear
pilgrimage that has become part magnet for anarchic defiance of
the authorities and part token of Germans' deep concern over the
perils of atomic power".
</P>
<P>
Police officials and some politicians maintain that alongside
peaceful demonstrators, the protest has also drawn in others who
see the occasion as a pretext for violent confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Against that argument, the Greens Party, which is in opposition
in Bonn, maintains that the issue is not so much the transport of
nuclear waste as the use of nuclear power in general.
</P>
<P>
"There is only one alternative, to abolish nuclear power in the
face of popular protest," Gunda Roestel, a leader of the Greens,
said earlier.
</P>
<P>
That notion might prove to be unpractical, because nuclear
power covered 34 percent of energy supply in Germany last year,
the largest single contributor to the energy needs in the country.
</P>
<P>
But as anti-nuclear protest gathering momentum and turning more
violent, the security costs soared. Authorities say security for
the transport this time will cost German taxpayers some 100
million German marks (60 million U.S. dollars). A similar
transport in 1996 ran up a 46 million mark bill, compared with 25
million marks for a 1995 shipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
