<HEADLINE> Syrian FM Meets With Japanese Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq
al-Shara met here today with a visiting Japanese envoy and they
discussed issues on bilateral relations and matters of mutual
concern.
</P>
<P>
According to a Syrian Foreign Ministry spokesman, al-Shara
discussed with Hiroshi Apayashi, special envoy of Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, relations between Syria and Japan,
the Middle East peace process and other matters of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources in Damascus said the Japanese envoy's visit
to Syria aims to seek Syrian support for the handover to Japan of
five Japanese, who have been arrested by the Lebanese authorities
and identified as members of the Japanese Red Army, an alleged
extremist leftist organization.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese officials denied earlier that the Lebanese security
forces had taken into custody any members of the "Red Army" in a
search-and-arrest campaign agaisnt Asians after obtaining
information on a clandestine group falsifying documents and entry
visas.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese envoy told reporters in his earlier visit to
Beirut that the identities of these people should be
distinguished and the Lebanese and Japanese governments were
working together in order to reach results "as soon as possible."
</P>
<P>
The envoy, who arrived in Damascus Tuesday evening from the
Lebanese capital of Beirut, brought with him a letter from the
Japanese prime minister to Syrian President Hafez al-Assad, but
the content of the letter was not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Apayashi held talks in Beirut with Lebanese officials on the
issue of release of the five arrested Japanese. But Lebanese
officials told him that they will be tried in Lebanon on charges
of forging illegal Lebanese residence documents, and that the
issue of their handover to Japan necessitates a political
decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
