<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Forecast to See Fastest Air Traffic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 5 (Xinhua) -- China will experience the
world's fastest air travel growth over the next 20 years,
forecast the top aircraft producer Boeing Commercial Airplane
Group.
</P>
<P>
The air traffic in China is expected to grow at 8.7 percent
annually in the next two decades, according to Boeing's 1997
edition of "Current Market Outlook", which was released today. The
 air travel within the country is predicted to grow at 10.3
percent every year while the international traffic to and from
China, at six percent.
</P>
<P>
China will purchase one out of every ten airplanes to be
assembled in the next 20 years, according to the 1997
Outlook. China will add 1,900 new jets worth of 124 billion US
dollars till 2016, while the world as a whole will add 16,160
jetliners worth of 1.1 trillion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Boeing report said that the Asia-Pacific region will
outpace other parts of the world in air travel growth, with an
annual forecast of 6.6 percent. The worldwide air travel is likely
 to increase 4.9 percent per year between now and 2016.
</P>
<P>
"The industry continues on the upswing, with airlines ordering
airplanes to meet increasing traffic and accommodate higher
passenger load levels," said Bruce Dennis, vice president of the
Marketing Department of Boeing. He noted that Boeing would produce
 40 airplanes per month in the fourth quarter of 1997, the highest
 ever monthly output.
</P>
<P>
The Asia-Pacific region will be the leading market for new
airplanes, taking one third of the total market in value, said the
 Boeing Outlook, which is published annually since 1965.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
