<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean President Reshuffles Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 5 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Young-sam
today replaced 10 out of 28 cabinet ministers in a wide-ranging
government shake-up following Tuesday's appointment of Koh Kun as
the new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The reshuffle comes as the president tries to overcome the
country's serious economic problems and in the wake of the Hanbo
Steel loans scandal.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Han Seung-soo was
replaced by veteran politician and former finance minister,
60-year-old Kang Kyong-shik who is a lawmaker from the ruling New
Korea Party.
</P>
<P>
Lim Chang-yuel replaces Ahn Kwang-kwoo as international trade
and industry minister, Choe Sang-yup takes over from Ahn Woo-mahn
as justice minister and Song Tae-ho replaces Ah Byung-young as
education minister.
</P>
<P>
Kwun Sook-il was appointed minister of science and technology,
Kang Oon-tae as the home affairs minister, and Lee Hwan-gyun as
the construction and transportation minister.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Lee Soo-song, who together with his cabinet
resigned Tuesday morning, was appointed by the president as
advisor of the ruling New Korean Party.
</P>
<P>
President Kim apologized on February 25 for the Hanbo Steel
scandal. The company collapsed in January under six billion
U.S. dollars of debt, much of which had been amassed allegedly by
paying kickbacks to influential people. Three of Kim's closest
associates have been arrested in connection with the scandal.
</P>
<P>
Kim had already replaced his chief secretary and three top
presidential aides before today's reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
The nomination on Tuesday of Koh Kun, former Seoul mayor and
Myongji University president, made Koh the fifth prime minister
since Kim took office in February 1993.
</P>
<P>
Kim's term will end after the presidential election at the end
of this year. He is barred by the constitution from seeking
reelection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
