<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Disperse Protesters by Water Cannons for Nuclear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of anti-nuclear protesters
were dispersed by police water cannons in northern Germany this
morning as they were trying to block the transport of nuclear
waste to a nearby storage depot.
</P>
<P>
The water cannons were sprayed as the demonstrators were
staging a peaceful overnight sit-in near the exit road from the
Dannenberg railway station, where nuclear waste from several
German power plants and a re-processing plant in France, was being
reloaded onto trucks to make its final journey to an interim
storage depot in Gorleben, some 19 kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
Police said they had to use the cannons to clear the road.
</P>
<P>
At another site along the route to Gorleben, 29 protesters were
arrested earlier Wednesday in clashes with the police.
</P>
<P>
Five policemen and three protesters were injured, police
reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Militant protesters on the road near the village of Quickborn
threw petrol bombs at a police vehicle, setting it ablaze.
</P>
<P>
Later, a home-made bomb was reportedly discovered by police
along the road and was defused shortly before the first of six
lorries carring nuclear waste containers moved out of the
Dannenberg railway station on their journey to Gorleben.
</P>
<P>
Police suspect the bomb was the work of a militant group of
anarchists called Autonomen.
</P>
<P>
The road through Quickborn was believed to be the route the
convoy will take because the alternative southern route had
already been blocked by local farmers with tractors and other
heavy equipment. Protesters had also dug deep holes into the road.
</P>
<P>
With violence growing, it was uncertain if the nuclear waste
could reach Gorleben by Wednesday evening as originally planned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
