<HEADLINE> Li Peng Confers with Legislators from Shaanxi (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Premier Li Peng today confered
with legislators from northwest China's Shaanxi Province on a wide
range of topics, which covered agriculture, state-owned
enterprises, aid to the needy, and social security system.
</P>
<P>
The legislators, who are here attending the Fifth Session of
the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC), China's legislature,
were also joined by Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo and senior Party
official Ding Guangen.
</P>
<P>
After several legislators talked about Shaanxi's achievements
and problems in agricultural development, retooling of state-owned
enterprises, and establishment of the social security system,
vice-premier Wu made some explanations to the existing problems of
state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Describing difficulties faced by some of these enterprises an
inevitable outcome of the shift in economic structure and of
market changes, Wu noted that practice has proved that state
enterprises are fully capable of adapting themselves to the
socialist market economic structure well.
</P>
<P>
"A large number of state-owned enterprises have developed and
grown in strength through reforms and market competition, and we
are confident that the situation of the enterprises this year will
be better than in 1996," he said.
</P>
<P>
Giving consent to Wu's words, Premier Li said that it is a
major task for Shaanxi, one of the country's old industrial bases
specialized in the machine-building industry to invigorate
state-owned enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
