<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe Needs Common Approach to Asylum Seekers: EC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- European Union countries should
work out a common approach to the issue of providing temporary
asylum to refugees, the European Commission (EC) said today.
</P>
<P>
The commission says the bloc needs to be better prepared for
the next possible mass influx of refugees into the EU and a common
approach in terms of time limits, social welfare and housing
should to be agreed in advance.
</P>
<P>
The EC, the executive body of the EU, says its new proposal
published today -- Joint Action on the Temporary Protection of
Displaced Persons -- aims at creating a framework for common
decision making between the member states regarding the opening
up, prolongation and phasing out of temporary asylum regimes.
</P>
<P>
The proposal also seeks to establish a minimum threshold as
regards rights and benefits for temporary refugees, including
access to the labour market, education, social welfare, housing
and conditions for family reunification.
</P>
<P>
There is currently no common approach among EU member states in
this area, and time limits as well as the status, rights and
benefits of those under temporary protection vary greatly from one
member state to another.
</P>
<P>
The conflict in former Yugoslavia resulted in unprecedented
numbers of displaced persons. Approximately two million people
fled from Bosnia, of which some 800,000 asked for asylum in the EU.
</P>
<P>
"There was no real co-operation between member states when the
mass influx from Bosnia occurred...Next time we are faced with
such a situation, we have to make sure that a fair and dignified
reception can be offered in all our member states," said Anita
Gradin, Home and Justice Affairs Commissioner.
</P>
<P>
The commission also pointed out that the proposed joint action,
which is intended for future situations, has no bearing on people
already under temporary protection, for example those who fled the
conflict in Bosnia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
