<HEADLINE> Nepali Opposition to Vote Against Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Lawmakers of Nepal's main
opposition party will vote against a motion to be tabled Thursday
in the lower house by Prime Minister Sher Bahadur Deuba to seek a
vote of confidence for his coalition government, a party leader
said today.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist Leninist,
CPN-UML), which is the largest party in the country's parliament,
decided at a meeting here today to order its MPs to vote against
the prime minister's confidence motion, Chief Whip of the CPN-UML
Devi Ojha said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also condemned the government's earlier decision to
postpone local elections, according to Ojha.
</P>
<P>
The three-party coalition, led by Deuba's Nepali Congress (NC)
party, last month decided to postpone the local elections till
after the introduction of new decentralization acts, which are
expected to give more autonomy to local administration bodies.
</P>
<P>
The on-going winter session of the lower house is also expected
to discuss and approve some important bills including those on
decentralization.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Deuba is scheduled to table a confidence motion
for his government Thursday at the house session as the coalition
had been reduced to a minority status by an opposition challenge
last December.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the government would obtain the vote of
confidence with a not-so-comfortable majority in the 205-seat
lower house where the opposition party holds 90 seats.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
