<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Speed up State-owned Enterprise Equitization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The government should speed up the
process of selling shares in state-owned enterprises to raise more
money for investment and improve the profits of the companies
involved, a senior official of the Communist Party of Vietnam
(CPV) said today.
</P>
<P>
The process, known as equitization in Vietnam, remains a
crucial task in the country's current "renovation," Nguyen Tan
Dung, a member of the Standing Board of the CPV Politburo and
chief of the Economic Commission of the CPV Central Committee,
said in an article in the Communist Review magazine.
</P>
<P>
He said equitization would increase the efficiency of the
public sector and ensure its leading role in Vietnam's economy.
</P>
<P>
Two or three businesses should be equitized under each
ministry, in each sector or region in 1997-98 to pave the way for
vigorous equitization in subsequent years, Dung said in the
article.
</P>
<P>
But he said equitization did not mean privatization. The
process is aimed at mobilizing more money for investment and
helping businesses raise profits for the government - rather than
for individuals.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam decided to equitize a number of state-owned enterprises
after the country embarked on its economic reform program, known
as "renovation," to create a market economy.
</P>
<P>
In the past three years, 10 state-owned enterprises have been
equitized, with the state retaining a stake of between 18 and 30
percent, employees holding 33-50 percent, and others, 20-40
percent.
</P>
<P>
Dung said since they were equitized, these businesses have
improved their overall performance and employees have particularly
benefited.
</P>
<P>
In addition, state control over these enterprises has improved,
more employment has been created and the role of employees in
management and inspection has been increased, Dung said.
</P>
<P>
But he said there were still too few companies lining up for
equitization, a lack of legal documentation and procedures about
equitization. The government should rectify this and give
preferential treatment to newly-equitized enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Promotes Software Industry Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Board of Investment (BOI) of
Thailand today announced that the government will give promotional
privileges to the development of the software industry.
</P>
<P>
Staporn Kavitanon, secretary general of the BOI, which is
chaired by Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh, said the BOI
considered that the software industry is of strategic importance
to the future of Thailand's economy due to its role in supporting
the development of information technology (IT).
</P>
<P>
The privileges will include exemption from import duty on
machinery and an eight-year corporate income tax holiday,
regardless of location, according to a BOI press release today.
</P>
<P>
The aim of offering privileges to the software industry is to
increase the industry's competitiveness with neighboring
countries, to prepare for the rapid growth of the domestic market,
and to facilitate production for export.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's software market is projected to triple to 9 billion
baht, or 270 million US dollars, by 1999,
</P>
<P>
Software projects, such as software development, software
production, software adjustment and maintenance systems,
multimedia software production and data entry services (including
accounting, graphics, photographs, voice data, or software
documentation excluding printing.)
</P>
<P>
Software industrial parks will also be eligible for special
privileges if they use high-speed fiber optic main communications
system for the entire park, and high-speed lines for domestic and
international communications.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
