<HEADLINE> CPP, Funcinpec Patching up Strained Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's co-prime ministers
today had an informal luncheon together in a sign of patching up
the deteriorating relations between the two partners in the
current coalition.
</P>
<P>
Second Prime Minister Hun Sen told reporters after their
luncheon just outside the capital that "both prime ministers have
committed themselves to returning to the past," referring to the
years from 1993 to 1995 when his Cambodian People's Party and the
Funcinpec Party led by First Prime Minister Norodom Ranariddh
cooperated in the drive for national reconciliation and
reconstruction following the U.N.-monitored elections.
</P>
<P>
The luncheon, following a meeting of the council of ministers
and attended by all its participants, seemed to be designed to
create good atmosphere favorable to restoring the partnership
between the two parties.
</P>
<P>
The relationship between the two parties began to deteriorate
early last year when the Funcinpec voiced at their congress the
demand for power-sharing at all government levels and the
worsening of their relations climaxed at the bloodshed conflict
last month in Battambang province between soldiers loyal to the
two parties respectively.
</P>
<P>
The agreement reached at the High command meeting last week on
a joint commission solving the Battambang conflict and reviewing
the commune elections law have stepped up the momentum to improve
relations between the two parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
