<HEADLINE> Philippine PC Sales Increase in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The total value of personal
computer sales in the Philippines grew by 35 percent last year to
314.28 million U.S. dollars from 232.69 million dollars in 1995,
according to a latest study by the International Data Corp. (IDC)
Phils.
</P>
<P>
The study by the information technology market research firm
showed that unit sales were up slightly, with 187,768 personal
computers of all types sold last year.
</P>
<P>
IDC Phils. General Manager Rommel Carlos said in the study that
the country's PC sales growth rate was the highest among the ASEAN
members.
</P>
<P>
However, the country was placed last (excluding Brunei) in
terms of real sales value.
</P>
<P>
PCs based on Intel Pentium processors also took the lion's
share of PCs sold last year, amounting to 140,098 units.
</P>
<P>
Most of the PCs sold were also desktops as 165,608 desktop PCs
valued at 251.7 million dollars were sold last year, the study
said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, up to 16,357 portable or notebook PCs were
shipped and they were valued at 37.79 million dollars, it said.
</P>
<P>
The brisk sale of notebooks could be attributed to the adoption
of portable PCs as mainstream business computing machines.
</P>
<P>
PC server sales were valued at 24.79 million dollars, with
5,803 units sold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
