<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Map Up Better Tool in Analyzing Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
mapping up a better tool that will enable economic planners to
project more accurately the impact particularly of wage and oil
price adjustments in the overall inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
The new "input-output" table will be based on the new structure
of the economy, Socioeconomic Planning Secretary Cielito Habito
said today in an interview with the Philippine News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The current paradigm the country used is based on the 1988
structure of the economy. Under such a scheme, economic planners
tend to overestimate the impact of adjustments, particularly wage
and oil prices, Habito said.
</P>
<P>
He said liberalization had resulted in substantial reform in
the economy and the impact of petroleum was no longer as strong as
the old structure would have provided.
</P>
<P>
Since 1988 when more structural change in the economy
transpired, the psychological impact of such adjustments has been
severely moderated.
</P>
<P>
The National Statistical Coordination Board is now devising a
more updated input-output table based on the country's current
economic structure and incorporate all the economic programs and
policies being undertaken by the government, according to Habito.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
