<HEADLINE> South China City to Increase Produce Supply for Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Shenzhen, a city bordering Hong
Kong, will increase investment in agriculture to make sure that
the city can ship over 1.2 billion Hong Kong dollars worth of
produce and fish to Hong Kong this year.
</P>
<P>
According to Yuan Ruwen, the city's vice-mayor, the figure will
be an increase of 10 percent over last year. He told reporters
that the increased investment will be used to build more modern
farms for "vegetable basket commodities", including a 666-hectare
vegetable farm, fish ponds with a combined area of 1,333 hectares,
and building fences for aquatic products in Shenzhen's offshore
areas.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen's economic miracles have resulted from China's reform
and open-up drive, making it an important source of produce and
live animals for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Sources say that 40 percent of the live chickens, 70 percent of
fresh milk, 40 percent of the breeding pigs, and 25 percent of
fresh vegetables on the Hong Kong market come from Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
The city is investing in farm produce, and also speeding up
construction of five major support projects to ensure the smooth,
efficient shipping of goods from Shenzhen to Hong Kong, said the
vice-mayor.  
</P>
</TEXT>
