<HEADLINE> Samaranch to Lead IOC for Another Four Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Juan Antonio Samaranch will
remain as president of the International Olympic Committee (IOC)
for another four years, it was announced here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The IOC's executive committee asked Samaranch to remain as
president and the 76-year-old accepted.
</P>
<P>
"It was not difficult to say yes," said Samarach, who has been
president since 1980 and with his fourth reign he would lead the
IOC until 2001.
</P>
<P>
His re-election will be formally confirmed at the IOC Congress
in September.
</P>
<P>
IOC senior vice-president Marc Hodler said the executive
committee was unanimous in its decision to ask the former Spanish
diplomat to stand again.
</P>
<P>
"And we were delighted he said yes," added Hodler.
</P>
<P>
Last year Samaranch, first elected at the Moscow Games, secured
television deals worth 5.5 billion U.S. dollars, stretching to the
2008 Games. 
</P>
