<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambians Suffer from SAP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Zambians are now poorer due to the
Structural Adjustment Program (SAP), according to a survey by the
Program Against Malnutrition (PAM) of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that many families have been forced to alter
their budgets and about 70 percent of the households especially in
urban areas are buying less food, clothes, shoes and other daily
expensese.
</P>
<P>
Lunch time for 80 percent of the labor force is now an involuntary
fasting period, according to the survey carried out recently.
</P>
<P>
Families are spending less on drinks and snacks than before
and 75 percent of the households have completely terminated meat
consumption from their diet.
</P>
<P>
Middle class families' budget cuts are mainly on non-essential
goods like restaurent eating, coffee and other dear beverages,
imported goods such as olivers, wines and cheeses.
</P>
<P>
Low income families are now forced to concentrate on necessities
and about 60 percent of Lusaka households said they now shop in
cheaper markets regularly, says the survey.
</P>
<P>
A variety of items like radios, television sets, stoves,
refrigerators, toasters, pressing irons and fans have borken down and
many families cannot afford to have them repaired, it says.
enditem

=03051319

=03051326
NNNN
21:26 21:26 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
