<HEADLINE> Pakistan Prime Minister Vows to Eliminate Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistan government will
spare no efforts to eliminate crimes and provide peace and
security for the people, Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Eliminating crimes and providing peace and security are the
primary responsibility of the government, Sharif told the first
meeting of the new cabinet held earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
He directed cabinet members, provincial chief ministers and
other senior officials to make proposals for improving the law and
order situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said he was seeking advice on the enactment of new laws
wherever considered necessary for the purpose and if required, he
would opt for constitutional amendments to ensure peace and
security for the people.
</P>
<P>
Sharif also asked the Ministry of Law and Justice and other
ministries concerned to re-examine proposed legislation on the
prohibition of wasteful expenditure on marriages, prohibition of
smoking in public offices and amendments to laws to include
exemplary punishments for heinous crimes such as gang-rape and
child abuse.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet will meet again on Thursday to decide on measures
to combat lawlessness in the country.
</P>
<P>
In the first three months of this year Pakistan has suffered
four terrorist attacks which left a total of 22 people dead and
about 45 others injured.  
