<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- China's chemical industry expects
to increase eight percent in its output value to 270 billion yuan
in 1997, "the same as the national economic growth," according to
Gu Xiulian, Chinese minister of Chemical Industry.
</P>
<P>
China's chemical industry in the new fiscal year will reform
state firms, restructure the product mix, and increase the
export-oriented economy, improving things overall, today's China
Chemical Industry News quoted Gu as saying.
</P>
<P>
Priority will be given to chemicals for agriculture, and the
ministry plans to develop new chemical products for the
automobile, electronics, and textile industries.
</P>
<P>
Chemical production in 1996 reached 250 billion yuan, a rise of
10 percent over the previous year. The production of chemical
fertilizers nationwide hit a record high of 25 million tons, as
did pesticide, at 350,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Experts with the Ministry of Chemical Industry estimate that
demand for chemical fertilizers this year will be 31.51 million
tons.  
