<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania and Japan have
opened a new chapter of mutual cooperation, starting 30 years
ago, following the end of the two countries' high level policy
talks here recently, an editorial of Daily News said today.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania and Japan have agreed to strengthen their cooperation
in such key areas as agriculture, small-scale industries, basic
education, primary health care, population problems and the
HIV/AIDS scourge, the editorial said.
</P>
<P>
Japan has been offering aid to Tanzania in the form of loans,
grants and technical assistance to support operations in the
sectors of transport, energy, agriculture, water,
telecommunications, natural resources and environment.
</P>
<P>
Japan has provided considerable resources to support these
programs by offering equipment, experts and technical
know-how, the editorial noted.
</P>
<P>
The editorial said that Japan has also provided food aid and
other forms of support.
</P>
<P>
"We have also been delighted to learn that Japan continues to
consider Tanzania as one of the most important countries in
Africa which deserve assistance under a new development strategy
by Japan", the editorial said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said Tanzania has been picked as one of the
six developing countries around the world to receive assistance
from Japan under a new strategy. 
