<HEADLINE> College Grads in China Face Unbalanced Job Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Some 900,000 college students will
have to deal with a topsy-turvy market when they try to find jobs
in July.
</P>
<P>
This year, Chinese enterprises will face the largest number of
college graduates since the founding of New China in 1949,
said an official with the State Education Commission.
</P>
<P>
Some 50,000 of them are graduate students working on master's
or doctor's degrees, and the rest are graduates of two- or
four-year college courses, he said.
</P>
<P>
The supply of graduate students falls short of demand, but the
supply of two-year graduates exceeds demand, while the number of
four- or five-year graduates seems to be in balance.
</P>
<P>
College students who majored in engineering, medicine, or
teaching face a fairly easy future, but those who studied
agriculture, history, finance, and some natural sciences will have
a harder time getting jobs.
</P>
<P>
This year, the State Education Commission did not hold a
national conference to supply information on jobs to college
students. Instead, some colleges have held direct talks with
enterprises to try to help their students find jobs.
</P>
<P>
Some 860,000 college students graduated last year, about 35,000
fewer than in 1995. Most Chinese students find jobs by the end of
June, and then graduate in July with job offers at the
enterprises or institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu, Mubarak Start Talks in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu held talks here today on
the peace process, particularly on a new housing project in East
Jerusalem which threatened to block the Middle East peace march.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu came exactly a week after Israel decided to set up
6,500 Jewish homes in Har Homa, a tree-covered hill in East
Jerusalem, taken by Israel in the 1967 Middle East War.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Mubarak is expected to urge Netanyahu to
shun any step on Jerusalem before reaching a relevant agreement
with the Palestinians in the final status talks due to start in
a few weeks, but the Har Homa issue has put it in doubt.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak has said he fears violence would flare up because of
Israel's new construction plan in East Jerusalem, which the
Palestinians want to have as the capital of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
But the president said he hopes to convince Netanyahu of the
risks involved in the settlement-construction process and its
adverse effect on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to exchange views and make him aware of what
could happen if the process reached a collapse," he said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"As to what we can do (if we fail to convince him), will we
declare war? No, nobody wants war, we are talking with Israel. So
I will explain what the consequences will be in the near future,"
he affirmed.
</P>
<P>
Viewed as an Israeli bid to tighten grip on the third holiest
city of Islam, the Har Homa plan already sparked wide-spread
Palestinian demonstrations and worldwide criticism.
</P>
<P>
Despite Mubarak's assurances that there is no problem between
Israel and Egypt and he only wants to create dialogue with Israel,
the Palestinian National Authority, Jordan and Egypt have set a
two-week deadline for Israel to cancel the settlement plan.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who has an different concept of peace with the
Palestinians, has defended the project as a move to alleviate a
shortage of housing for Arabs and Jews in the city.
</P>
<P>
Instead of backing down on Har Homa, the Israeli leader, on the
eve of his visit to Cairo, warned that a Palestinian state at this
stage will destroy the whole peace process.
</P>
<P>
Though Netanyahu might be sensible enough to consult Mubarak on
the issue, a change of mind seems out of the question.
</P>
<P>
Besides Jerusalem, the meeting is also expected to deal with
the Syrian-Israeli peace talks, frozen for 12 months. Syria
insisted on the full return of the Golan Heights, a strategic
plateau captured by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
Israel rejected the position and said it is willing to discuss
partial withdrawal with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak is expected to urge Netanyahu to come up with a new
formula to persuade Syria to return to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
The meeting with Netanyahu precedes Mubarak's March 10 trip to
Washington, which would also deal with the Mideast peace process,
especially Jerusalem and resumption of the Israeli-Syrian peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, a key mediator in the peace process, is the first Arab
country to make peace with Israel, in 1979, but ties remain cool
between them.
</P>
<P>
At a time, Israel accused Egypt of hamstringing the
Palestinians on reaching the Hebron agreement and tried to exclude
Egypt from mediation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
