<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislator Calls for Preservation of Forests at River Origin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese legislator has called
for utmost attention to be paid to the preservation of forests at the
origin of the Yangtze River, the longest in China.
</P>
<P>
Chen Yaoren, a deputy from Gansu who is attending the ongoing
session of the National People's Congress (NPC), warned that soil
erosion in the Bailongjiang region may turn the Yangtze into a
second Yellow River, China's second longest, whose name derives
from its color as a result of the large amounts of soil it
carries to the sea.
</P>
<P>
The Bailongjiang forest region, at the juncture of the three
provinces of Gansu, Sichuan and Shaanxi and in an area where both
rivers originate, include the nature reserve for the precious
giant panda and the pristine Jiuzhaigou scenic zone.
</P>
<P>
Chen, vice director of the Gansu provincial forestry
department, suggested that the state allocate in the 1997-2000
period ten million yuan annually as a special fund to help
preserve the forests.
</P>
<P>
Chen, who spent 27 years working in this biggest timber
production base in northwest China and one of the eight major
forestry regions in the country, said that, given shrinking forest
resources in the area, according to a State Council decision,
annual amount of logging there has been cut by one third to
200,000 cu m since 1978.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, reduced logging has meant reduced work, and
the life of the 50,000 workers and their dependents has been
affected.
</P>
<P>
Chen suggested that the special fund be used to start new
businesses offering jobs for one fourth of the forest workers. The
function of the area administration, he said, will be shifted to
forest protection, afforestation and forest management.
</P>
<P>
He also proposed that the Bailongjiang forest region be
incorporated into the Yangtze River Shelter-Forest Project to
improve the environment at the upper reaches of the river and
maintain a clean origin for the Yangtze and Yellow rivers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
