<HEADLINE> Samaranch to Stand for IOC Presidential Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Juan Antonio Samaranch said on
Wednesday that he would stand for his fourth presidential election
of the International Olympic Committee and lead the IOC into the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch, who turns 77 in July, told a news conference that
the vote to be held in September. If he wins, the Spaniard has the
chance to complete 21 years in office after taking over the spot
in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch, who turned the Olympic movement into a successful
commercial outfit in the last two decades, has said for a while
that he would carry on if his health was in order.
</P>
<P>
He is not expected to face opposition in the election by the
IOC's members at a session to be held in Lausanne in September.
</P>
<P>
If he completes his fourth term in office he will be 81 by the
time the next election takes place in 2001. 
</P>
