<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC to Face Challenge From Non-OPEC Producers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 5 (Xinhua) - The global oil production is
expected to soar from the current 5 million barrels per day (bpd)
to 8 million bpd over the next decade, posing serious challenge
to the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
During the fifth annual Middle East Petroleum and Gas
Conference which concluded here Tuesday, international oil
industry sources said the increase, which is mainly contributed
by the non-OPEC producers, will impose big pressure on
production-limited OPEC countries.
</P>
<P>
OPEC producers in the Gulf is likely to keep their current
level of some 26 million bpd in the next ten years in order to
sustain their present prices, while non-OPEC countries see no
such limitation and they can increase their production freely,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, non-OPEC production reached some 43 million bpd,
according to recent forecasts by the International Energy
Agency.
</P>
<P>
The forecast also showed non-OPEC production estimated for
1997 will be over 45 million bpd, or about 1.75 times the 26
million bpd of OPEC production for the same period.
</P>
<P>
Driving the increase in non-OPEC production is a greater level
of exploration and production (E&AMP;P) investment in non-OPEC countries,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
During the past five years, E&AMP;P investment in non-OPEC
countries is estimated to stand at over 200 billion U.S. dollars,
while E&AMP;P investment in OPEC countries was less than 45 billion
dollars for the same period, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Innovations in technology also allowed non-OPEC countries to
increase their oil production through lowering production costs
and expanding their geographic and geologic horizons.
</P>
<P>
Recent innovations such as horizontal drilling, floating
production systems and a host deep water technologies has cut
down costs of exploration, development and production, and in
regions where oil industry has been regarded as unprofitable is
turning profitable now, the sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
