<HEADLINE> Cambodian Rice Output Up: FAO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian rice output for 1996/97
is estimated at 3.39 million tons, about 2 percent above the
estimated 1995/96 production and 35 percent higher than the
average for the previous five years, according to the U.N. Food
and Agriculture Organization (FAO) here today.
</P>
<P>
An FAO and World Food Program mission visited Cambodia in
January this year to estimate the 1996/97 wet season rice harvest,
forecast the 1996/97 dry season rice production and evaluate the
national cereal outlook for 1997.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's total availability of rice for 1997 is estimated at
2.12 million tons while its requirement of rice for human
consumption, seed and feed is about 1.933 million tons, thus
leaving a surplus of 127,000 tons, the FAO said in a press
release.
</P>
<P>
1997 is the second consecutive year in which the country will
have a rice surplus after many years.
</P>
<P>
The mission concluded that Cambodia is definitely making
structural progress in food production, although it has not fully
overcome its crucial problem of food shortage.
</P>
<P>
The World Food Program estimated that no less than 265 communes
still require food aid, about 19 percent of all communes in the 18
main rice-growing provinces.
</P>
<P>
The mission stressed the country's need for a better irrigation
system and water control and for more investment in
infrastructure, especially rural roads.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
