<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmer Digs Out White Pottery of Tang Dynasty in Backyard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Zhang Yinqi, a farmer in a
small village in north China, never expected to dig up a treasure
trove of thousand-year-old white pottery while working in his
backyard.
</P>
<P>
The recent find, in Dongfengsi Village, Zhaoxian County in
Hebei Province, consists of 46 pieces of pottery in white or other
colors. A complete human skeleton was also found in the tomb, some
two meters underground.
</P>
<P>
The tomb was dated around the year 688 during the Tang Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
One-third of the sacrificial objects are pottery figures
dressed as officials, warriors, ethnic people, maids or women
musicians. They range from 40 to 50 cm in height.
</P>
<P>
Included are also animal figures which serve to guard the tomb,
a pottery pig, lion, camel, ox, horse, fish, sheep, dog and
household objects such as a pottery cart, grind and water
container.
</P>
<P>
Experts commented that the most representative of the objects
is a 59-cm tall pottery warrior standing on a oblong base. He is
wearing a helmet, his mouth is open and his eyes are wide, he has
a thick mustache and looks noble. His left arm bends in front of
his chest, and his hand is clenched. His right hand holds a
serpent whose head touchs the ground.
</P>
<P>
The facial expression and posture of the warrior demonstrate
the power of the Tang army, experts said.
</P>
<P>
The author of the pottery was found to be the same artist who
created the sacrificial objects in two tombs found earlier in the
city of Xintai in the province. Several similar one-chamber brick
tombs have been found in the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
