<HEADLINE> Kohl Meets U.S. Defence Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 5 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl met
here today with visiting U.S. Defence Secretary William Cohen,
praising the relations between Germany and the United States as
"outstanding."
</P>
<P>
Cohen is currently on his first trip abroad after becoming U.S.
defence chief. He is due to end his two-day stay in Germany today
after visiting U.S. military bases in southern Germany and meeting
U.S. military commanders in Stuttgart.
</P>
<P>
Cohen held talks Tuesday with his German counterpart Volker
Ruehe. According to him, it was possible that Washington might
eventually give up or share the command of southern NATO forces
with a European officer after several years -- an issue over which
the U.S. and France have been fighting over years.
</P>
<P>
In response to a German tentative, the new U.S. defence chief
said the U.S. was willing to review the matter in five, six or
seven years, while stressing that the command might still remain
in U.S. hands.
</P>
<P>
Cohen on Tuesday also affirmed the withdrawal of
U.S. peacekeeping troops in Bosnia in June, 1998 as planned. He
met on Monday in Pentagon with British Defence Secretary Michael
Portillo, who required the U.S. to remain in Bosnia, sharing with
its NATO allies in Europe the burden of peacekeeping there.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Cohen is expected to visit the air force base at
Aviano, Sicily, Tuzla in Bosnia and to meet with Italian Defence
Minister Beniamino Andreatta in Rome. He will end his first
foreign tour Friday after talks with NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana in Brussels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
