<HEADLINE> Industrial Corridor Takes Shape on Island </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, March 5 (Xinhua) -- An industrial corridor has taken
shape in the west part of Hainan, the largest island province in
China, after a massive construction effort that has lasted for
years.
</P>
<P>
West Hainan was an underdeveloped area until focus was centered
on the development of its abundant natural resources.
</P>
<P>
By taking advantage of offshore natural gas nearby, the Hainan
Natural Gas Chemical Fertilizer Plant has invested 2.5 billion
yuan (about 301 million US dollars) in setting up a fertilizer
plant.
</P>
<P>
The newly-completed plant is capable of producing 300,000 tons
of synthetic ammonia and 520,000 tons of urea annually. The plant,
which is the country's first producer of large granulated urea,
will generate an output value of one billion yuan per year.
</P>
<P>
By processing mangos and 30 other fruits on the island, the
Yefeng (Coconut Wind) company, jointly invested by Chinese and
foreign businessmen, has become a large enterprise group with an
annual output value of three billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Yangpu Economic Development Zone has invested 5.3 billion
yuan in setting up a 315,500-kw power plant and a power grid,
completing construction of 50 km long highways and underground
facilities, and leveling 18 square kilometers of land.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the zone made a breakthrough in inviting business for
its industrial projects; a group of chemical plants, with an
investment of nearly 10 billion yuan, are to be launched soon.
</P>
<P>
Since the province decided to set up more heavy industries in
the west and build an industrial corridor, the area's economy has
gained strong momentum.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the output value of six counties and cities in the
west and the Yangpu Economic Development Zone grew by 2.4 billion
yuan. The growth rates of Danzhou, Chengmai and Dongfang
respectively hit 13.8 percent, 22.5 percent and 28.4 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
