<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lassa Fever Kills Nine in Eastern Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Nine people died of lassa
fever in eastern Sierra Leone between December and February, a
Health Ministry official told Xinhua today in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
Alentine Kawa, a health education officer, said 59 people,
admitted at the Kenema Government Hospital, are currently
seriously ill.
</P>
<P>
"There is evidence of more people suffering from the disease,
but they are living in outlying villages," he said.
</P>
<P>
The situation would have worsened, added Kawa.
</P>
<P>
However, the medical authorities in Freetown said the
situation "is not very alarming and it could be contained."
</P>
<P>
"It is important to avoid coming in contact with patients who
display the signs and symptoms because the disease is transmitted
through a patient's vomit or other fluids from his body," said a
bulletin released by the Health Ministry.
</P>
<P>
A lassa fever research center is based in Guinea bordering on
Sierra Leone where all related cases are handled in collaboration
with personnel from the World Health Organization and the center
for disease control in Atlantan Georgia in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Lassa fever is a kind of epidemic caused by Lassa virus. The
disease was first found in Lassa Village in Nigeria. enditem

=03051144

=03051150
NNNN
19:50 19:50 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
