<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace-keepers Worry About Revenge Killings in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- As life returns to normal in
Liberia and hundreds of displaced and exiled citizens back home
daily after the successful disarmament, revenge killings of
former faction fighters have aroused international concern.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here today, at least six former
fighters were hacked to death by angry villagers who accused them
of mass killings and harassment during the civil war, which
claimed the lives of more than 150,000 people in the West African
country.
</P>
<P>
In Monrovia, capital of Liberia, Commander Major-General
Victor Malu of the West African Peace-Keeping Force (ECOMOG) said
on Tuesday reports reaching ECOMOG had indicated that the said
citizens were going about, armed with cutlasses and sticks in the
name of vigilante groups, waylaying known former fighters and in
some cases inflicting bodily injuries on them.
</P>
<P>
Such incidents occurred especially in areas around Sass Town
and Degbeh village in Bomi and Grand Cape Mount Countries,
northwestern Liberia, the Nigerian general said.
</P>
<P>
The situation has forced the flight of hundreds of ex-fighters
to their surrounding bushes. Some are said to have arrived in
Monrovia from villages they once occupied before the disarmament
exercise.
</P>
<P>
"ECOMOG views this conduct as highly negative and completely
detrimental to its efforts to achieve a lasting reconciliation
and peace for all Liberians," said Malu.
</P>
<P>
"The chasing around and molesting of former fighters who have
been disarmed in the quest for national peace is criminal,
unethical and illegal," he warned.
</P>
<P>
The force commander urged all Liberians to imbibe a spirit of
forgiveness and reconciliation as that is the only way to speed
up the recovery of the Liberian nation from the devastation by
the civil war.
</P>
<P>
"Rather than molest disarmed fighters because of their
horrible acts in the past, such citizens concerned, and indeed
all Liberians should divert their energies into furnishing ECOMOG
with information about hidden arms so that we can recover all
unsurrendered weapons and further make the country safe for all,
especially as we embark on the process," he said.
</P>
<P>
Disarmament and demobilization of Liberia's rival factions
ended in early February this year. During the exercise, more than
30,000, or 91 percent of the factional fighters, were disarmed by
Nigerian-led ECOMOG, while some 14,156 pieces of arms, 1.65
million ammunitions and 4,369 bombs were recovered.
</P>
<P>
Currently preparations are underway for the country's general
elections scheduled for May 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
Three former Liberian rival warlords, Charles Taylor, Alhaji
Kromah and George Boley, have resigned from the ruling Council of
State to contest for the presidency in the forthcoming national
polls.
</P>
<P>
All three were former vice-chairmen of the interim government
and leaders of major warring factions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
