<HEADLINE> DPRK Opposes Japan's Security Council Aim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) today stressed its opposition to Japan's wish to
become a permanent member of the United Nation's Security Council.
</P>
<P>
An article, published in the official newspaper, Rodong Sinmun,
said Japanese leaders recently advocated their so-called Japanese
"values" and "philosophy," claiming they would guide the world
through the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
If Japan, which had moved from being an economic power to a
military power, became a permanent member of the Security Council,
it would promote its hegemonism and power politics, and extend its
influence to the whole world, the article said.
</P>
<P>
The article also criticized Japan for creating the view of
equality with Germany on becoming a permanent member of the
Security of Council.
</P>
<P>
Japan and Germany couldn't be treated equally because they
treated the war crimes differently, it said.
</P>
<P>
So, Japan should start by admitting and compensating for its
crimes before bidding for a permanent membership in the Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
The article was published as Japan launched a promotion for its
aim to become a permanent member. 
</P>
</TEXT>
