<HEADLINE> China's Natural Protection Wins Praise From Overseas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIDAIHE (Hebei), March 5 (Xinhua) -- Delegates of overseas
environmental protection agencies today praised the achievements
China has scored in the field at the ongoing International
Workshop on Wetlands and Water-Bird Conservation held in coastal
Beidaihe, north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
Douglas Hykle, from the United Nations Environment Program,
said that China has contributed significantly to the global
natural protection work in the past decade, playing an influential
role in shouldering international responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
"I've been to China seven times, and find that the country's
public awareness of natural protection has improved," said Faizal
Parish, executive director of Wetlands International Asia Pacific.
</P>
<P>
He said it's amazing that China has increased the number of its
natural reserves to nearly 800 in less than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
"Two things have impressed me most," he noted. "One is that
China closed a large number of small-sized paper mills with
serious pollution problems last year, and the other is that so
many government officials in the country attended this symposium."
</P>
<P>
Faizal told Xinhua News Agency that wetlands protection is
still an unfamiliar practice in many countries, but China realized
its importance several years ago.
</P>
<P>
"In this field, China is at the forefront," he said.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from the World Wide Fund For Nature Hong Kong said
that they are encouraged by the fact that China has spent a large
sums on protecting nature, which clearly illustrates the country's
dedication to the work.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jianwei, an official with the Chinese Ministry of
Forestry, said that planting trees and caring for birds are
popular hobbies in the country.
</P>
<P>
China is drafting its first desert law, which will redouble the
country's efforts to protect nature, Chen said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
