<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> R&AMP;D Contribution to GDP Still Low in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Research and Development
(R&AMP;D) contribution to Gross Domestic Product (GDP) in Malaysia is
still low, science adviser in the Prime Minister's Department Omar
Abdul Rahman said today.
</P>
<P>
The overall national R&AMP;D effort is only around 0.8 percent of
GDP, against the 1.5 percent targeted under the Sixth Malaysia
Plan (1991- 1995), he said at an R&AMP;D symposium here.
</P>
<P>
He said the targeted 25 percent contribution by the private
sector to the nation's R&AMP;D effort has also not been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Hence, there is an increasing need to create more smart
partnerships between the public and private sectors as well as
local and foreign companies to intensify R&AMP;D efforts towards
promoting the growth of technology-based industries in Malaysia,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He regretted that "the R&AMP;D awareness is also not there despite
the increasing public sector allocation to R&AMP;D -- 400 million
ringgit (about 160 million U.S. dollars) under the 5th Malaysia
Plan (1986-1990), 600 million ringgit (about 240 million dollars)
under the 6th Malaysia Plan and 1 billion ringgit (about 400
million dollars) under the 7th Malaysia Plan (1996-2000)."
</P>
<P>
According to the Malaysian Business Trends Survey Report 1996
published by the Malaysian Institute of Management (MIM), 30
percent of 166 respondents had no R&AMP;D activities at all while the
rest spent less than 1.9 percent on R&AMP;D.
</P>
<P>
This is far behind when compared with foreign multi-national
corporations which spend no less than 10 percent of their total
annual company expenditure for R&AMP;D.
</P>
<P>
Omar said through mastery of technology will the country
control its own destiny in the face of the inevitable competitive
forces from globalization.
</P>
<P>
Information technology (IT) could enhance the country's Total
Factor Productivity (TFP), the measure for productivity driven
growth (as opposed to input-driven growth), which reflects
technological content of the productive sectors, he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's TFP was also low at 16 percent of the total GDP
growth during the period 1960-1990 and under the 7th Malaysia Plan
the country has a target TFP of 41 percent, according to the
adviser.
</P>
<P>
Omar said the absorption of technology management by the public
and private sectors and foreign companies could help the promoted
smart partnerships to succeed as it can smoothen technology
transfer and technology co-development.
</P>
<P>
He called on the small- and medium-scale industries (SMIs) to
start their R&AMP;D programs now by sourcing financing from the 1
billion ringgit (400 million dollars) fund under the
Intensification of Research in Priority Areas and Microelectronics
Institute of Malaysia allocations.
</P>
<P>
The related programs involving the public and private sectors
which are being promoted include setting up R&AMP;D companies,
cooperative research centers, industry-specific research
institutes, R&AMP;D syndication and technological universities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nuclear Power Plant Repaired in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Indian scientists claimed to
have developed the technology required to repair nuclear power
plants and increase their life span by 15 years, The Times of
India reported today.
</P>
<P>
Scientists at the Rajasthan Atomic Power Project in India's
Rajasthan State said they have been successful in repairing one of
the power-generating units which was shut down three years ago.
</P>
<P>
They said the unit would start generating power again by April.
</P>
<P>
The first unit of the atomic power station was closed down in
1994 because of a leakage in the coolant tubes of its reactor,
resulting in the leakage of heavy water and helium gas.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear scientists from some Western countries had suggested
that the plant be closed down and "buried" as it was impossible to
repair the tubes.
</P>
<P>
They had claimed that any attempt to repair them would cost
millions of dollars with no guarantee of success.
</P>
<P>
Despite this, the Indian scientists proceeded to change six of
the eight damaged coolant tubes at a cost of about 200 million
rupees (about 5.7 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The scientists assessed the damage caused to the tubes by
inserting a remote-control instrument and studied possible
remedial measures.
</P>
<P>
A specially-designed gasket was inserted into the coolant
chambers using robots, enabling the scientists to plug the leakage
in the tubes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Jobless Rate Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The jobless rate between November
1996 and January 1997 in Macao dropped to 3.8 percent, the latest
official statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Macao Census and Statistics Department
show that the unemployment rate in Macao declined one percent from
4.8 percent in mid-1996 to 3.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The rate of half-employment fell to 0.5 percent between
November 1996 and January 1997, down from 0.7 percent between
September and November 1996.
</P>
<P>
During the period of November 1996 and January 1997, about 50.3
percent of Macao residents were labor population, 0.1 percentage
points lower compared with the October 1996-December 1996 period.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for Economy and Coordination of the Macao Government
Vitor Pessoa said Macao's economy began to show a revival in the
latter half of 1996 following a two-year spell of slowdown.
</P>
<P>
Both imports and exports in the fourth season of 1996 rose
compared with the same period of 1995. Bank loans increased while
inflation dropped from 8.6 percent in 1995 to 4.8 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
