<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Rejects E.U. Greenhouse Gas Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer today criticized a European Union (E.U.) plan to
reduce global greenhouse gas emissions for not treating all
countries equally.
</P>
<P>
Downer said while answering a question in the parliament that
the E.U. plan allows individual European nations flexibility in
meeting the target by 2010 but does not offer the same flexibility
to other countries.
</P>
<P>
Australia is resisting binding targets for reducing greenhouse
gas emissions being pushed by Europe and the United States in
international climate change talks.
</P>
<P>
It argues that it will be asked to bear a disproportionate
share of the cost of combating global warming because it is a
major carbon-based energy exporter.
</P>
<P>
Downer told the parliament that the European plan does offer
flexibility for the development needs of individual countries, but
only in Europe. It allows Portugal to increase greenhouse
emissions by 40 percent, Greece by 30 percent and Spain by 17
percent while Australia would be required to conform to the
15-percent overall target.
</P>
<P>
"The 15-percent target is unrealistic and we see it as more of
a negotiating tactic by the European Union. The proposal is
frankly unworkable because it doesn't provide a sound framework
for long-term cooperative arrangements to address the climate
change issue," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
