<HEADLINE> Singapore Steps Up Efforts to Become International </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government is
stepping up its efforts to develop the country into an
International Exhibition City by the year 2000, as it is embarking
on a two-year program to strengthen the software component of its
exhibition management services industry.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Trade Development Board (TDB) said today that
this program was integral to realize the national vision of
developing Singapore as an international exhibition city by the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
For Singapore to enhance the software element of the exhibition
management services sector, the TDB noted that it will need the
presence of high quality mega trade fairs which can rival other
competing shows in the region and command international
participation.
</P>
<P>
"This aspect is crucial in Singapore's ability to pull in
international trade buyers and sellers to its shores," it said.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the TDB said strategic efforts should be made in
creating a framework for public-private sector partnership,
raising international awareness, setting internationally accepted
performance standards for trade fairs in Singapore, and enhancing
the image of Singapore exhibition management services companies
and trade fairs.
</P>
<P>
It said that it is also important to enhance industry
development and support, and broaden the scope of exhibition
management services companies and trade fairs.
</P>
<P>
Singapore is now host to many international trade shows, as 18
out of the 46 Asian trade shows recognized by the Union des Foires
International (UFI) are currently held in Singapore, the TDB said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
