<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crime Rate Unacceptably High in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Although serious crime rates
have dropped in nine out of 20 categories last year over 1995,
the crime levels in South Africa remain unacceptably high,
according to a quarterly crime statistics issued today.
</P>
<P>
Categories which saw a decrease included murder, car
hijacking, drug-related offenses and aggravated robbery, while
four kinds of crimes, including rape and serious assault,
increased.
</P>
<P>
Murders in the country fell to 61.1 per 100,000 last year
against 64.6 in 1995 and 66.6 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi attributed this
decline to the success of police task groups which have targeted
organized political violence.
</P>
<P>
Car hijackings were down by 18.6 percent in Gauteng Province,
where three quarters of the hijackings occurred, and was the only
province in which comparable statistics were available.
</P>
<P>
Robbery with aggravating circumstances dropped from 210.8
cases per 100,000 in 1994 to 159.2 last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, fraud, forgery, embezzlement, mal-appropriation and
other commercial crimes remained virtually stable at 75.3 cases
per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
However, reported rapes were increased from 105.3 per 100,000 in
1994 to 115.2 in 1995 and 119.5 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the statistics in Pretoria Tuesday night, Mufamadi
said he was pleased with the stabilizing or declining trend in
most serious crime categories, but worried about the unacceptably
high crime rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
