<HEADLINE> British Firm Wins Nigerian Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- British company TAD Eurotube has
won a 15.6-million-U.S.-Dollar contract to supply alloy, carbon
and stainless steel pipes to Nigeria's 3.8-billion-Dollar
Liquefied Natural Gas prjoect, the "Guardian" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report indicated that the contract was signed as early as
in last December but was only made known to local media on
Tuesday, when TAD Eurotube officials arrived in Lagos, together
with a group of British oil and gas companies seeking business
chances in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
It said that the TAD Eurotube contract is part of a series of
sub-contracts awarded by TSKJ Nigeria Limited, an international
consortium now responsible for the contruction of the Liquefied
Natural Gas plant on Bonny Island, Rivers State, in south
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's National Engineering and Technical Company and South
Korea's Daewoo Corporation have won such sub-contracts earlier.
</P>
<P>
The Bonny plant is a major step by Nigeria to make a better
use of its huge deposit of natural gas, a large quantity of which
is being flared daily by its many oilfields.
</P>
<P>
The TSKJ is an international consortium formed by businesses
from France, Italy, the United States and Japan. 
