<HEADLINE> CPPCC National Committee Holds 2nd Plenary Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Some members of the Eighth
National Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC) aired their views on topics of general concern
at the second plenary meeting of its annual session here today.
</P>
<P>
Present at the meeting were CPPCC National Committee
Chairman Li Ruihuan and Vice Premier Wu Bangguo.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Wenshou, vice chairman of the CPPCC National
Committee's Subcommittee for Handling Proposals, reported on the
handling of proposals submitted by members since the last
session of the National Committee.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yuzhao, executive vice chairman of the Subcommittee on
Economy, said the problem of a shortage of capital for state-owned
enterprises must be addressed to help them overcome difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The problem has been caused by an overheated real estate market
which consumes an immense amount of fund, debt entanglements among
enterprises, an increased stockpiling of goods, and non-performing
bank loans.
</P>
<P>
Hu Zhengguang, a member of the Standing Committee of the CPPCC
National Committee, suggested that economic cooperation between
Shenzhen and Hong Kong be increased, especially in urban
infrastructure and the connecting of the existing two passages, to
help maintain prosperity and stability in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Jin Jian, another Standing Committee member and an executive
vice chairman of the Subcommittee on Nationalities and Religion,
called for attention to problems existing in border trade.
</P>
<P>
Tsui Tsin-tong, a Hong Kong businessman, suggested that Hong
Kong's advantages as an international economic center be preserved
and developed after its return to China, and that the inland
continue to back Hong Kong's economy to maintain its prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Siwei, Chairman of the Central Committee of the China
Democratic National Construction Association, Jin Shuping,
Chairman of the All China Federation of Industry and Commerce, and
Gu Shengzu, a professor from Wuhan University, spoke on economic
restructuring, the creation of more job opportunities, and poverty
relief programs in cities. 
</P>
