<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Arrives in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu arrived here today amid mounting Arab and international
furor over a new Israeli settlement plan in East Jerusalem, which
threatens to stumble the whole peace process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu came exactly a week after Israel decided to set up
6,500 Jewish homes in Gabal Abu Ghoneim, a tree-covered hill in
East Jerusalem, which was seized by Israel in the 1967 Middle East
War.
</P>
<P>
The settlement project, which the former Labor government had
delayed under pressure, has sparked Palestinian demonstrations and
worldwide denouncement.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak said Netanyahu has caused
anger among the Egyptians to the extent that a visit to Israel
would be wrong, unless these policies could be changed.
</P>
<P>
Today's talks between the two leaders will delve into the peace
prospects in the Middle East region in light of the worsening
conditions as a result of the Israeli housing plan.
</P>
<P>
While Netanyahu could defend the project as a move to alleviate
a shortage of housing for Arabs and Jews in the city, Mubarak is
expected to urge him to shun any step regarding Jerusalem before
reaching a relevant agreement with the Palestinians on a solution
satisfying both parties.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said Monday that he would try his utmost to dissuade
Netanyahu from following through the decision during their meeting
today.
</P>
<P>
The visit is Netanyahu's second to Egypt since he held talks
with Mubarak after assuming office last June. Since then, Mubarak
has said he would not host the Israeli leader unless the
Palestinian-Israeli talks make progress on the long-delayed
Israeli partial pullback from the West Bank town of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Israel completed the Hebron withdrawal after it reached a deal
with the Palestinian national Authority on January 15. It is
committed to starting the first stage of redeployment in the rural
areas of the West Bank before March 7, a date Israel is very
likely to delay.
</P>
<P>
Besides the Palestinian-Israeli track, another topic listed
high on the meeting's agenda is the Israeli-Syrian peace talks,
frozen since last February. The two sides bicker over the fate of
the Golan Heights, a strategic plateau captured by Israel in the
1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has blamed Israel for the stalled talks and urged
Netanyahu to come up with a new formula that would persuade Syria
to return to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, a key mediator in the peace talks, signed a peace treaty
with Israel in 1979, but the bilateral ties remain cool. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
