<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Proposal Submission Key Means of Political Consultation (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Some figures of Non-Communist
parties and other members of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) National Committee today told of
their stories about advisory activities for the Communist Party
and the government.
</P>
<P>
During the past four years, approximately 10,000 proposals have
been set forth by 92 percent of the members of the Eighth CPPCC
National Committee, which is in its annual session in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
These proposals offer prescriptions for all types of "diseases"
in China, ranging from the strengthening of macro-economic control
to the control of swine cysticercosis.
</P>
<P>
"They have covered a wide-range of topics, and also scored
satisfactory achievements," said Gu Shengzu, a CPPCC National
Committee member the China Democratic National Construction
Association, one of the country's non-Communist parties.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that each good proposal had gone through a
process of deep pondering and meticulous designing.
</P>
<P>
Usually, proposals of the CPPCC National Committee members have
two major functions. One is to report major social problems with
great public interest and suggest ways of solution, and the other
is to offer the government advices on major issues concerning
national economy and people's livelihood.
</P>
<P>
The CPPCC National Committee today commended more than 100
members as "kings of proposals" for their active and effective
involvement in China's government and political affairs.
</P>
<P>
One of them was Ye Weizhen, a member of the non-Communist China
Democratic League, who was cited for two proposals regarding the
transformation of a seriously-polluted park in downtown Beijing
and the reform of China's social pension insurance system
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Before submitting any proposals, Ye said, the CPPCC members
usually study the government work report repeatedly in order to
find an appropriate topic, and then conduct meticulous and
down-to-earth investigations.
</P>
<P>
Gu Shengzu, who heads a population center of the prestigious
Wuhan University in central China'a Hubei Province, conducted a
survey at the cost of 500,000 yuan, before he wrote a proposal on
the administration of migrant population in China's urban areas,
which later drew much attention from the central authorities.
</P>
<P>
To prepare for a motion on the strengthening of quality
education, Wang Fuzhong made trips to different types of schools
and consulted officials with the State Education Commission and
educational experts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Proposal Submission Key Means of Political Consultation (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"A good proposal should have substantial content and a solid
basis, and write well and in good order," said member Wang Junyan
from a Hannan University in the country's southernmost province.
"But what's more important is feasibility. The proposal should
be rational and reasonable, and you can't propose anything that is
impossible to achieve in practical work."
</P>
<P>
But Member Chong Wing-king, chairman of the board of the Hong
Kong-based Yap Chau Holdings Ltd., said that there is also a kind
of "risk-taking proposals", which submitters should consider and
set forth long before others.
</P>
<P>
Four years ago, Chong put forth a proposal to call for
government attention to the reality of widening economic
differences between eastern and western China, and the proposal
won praises today.
</P>
<P>
Most proposals of the CPPCC National Committee members have
drawn due attention from government leaders and the relevant
departments, with problems they reported being solved quickly.
</P>
<P>
Some major Party and government policies and measures, such as
those on the promotion of ethical and cultural progress and the
easing of farmers' economic burden, could also be attributed
partly to proposals of the CPPCC National Committee.
</P>
<P>
Sometimes, however, the acceptance of a proposal takes time. Ye
Weizhen recalled that it took her a lot of efforts to convince
local officials of the measures Ye had suggested to clean the
polluted man-made lake.
</P>
<P>
"We are calling for increased attention to proposals submitted
by the CPPCC members," said Sun Fuling, vice-chairman of the CPPCC
National Committee.
</P>
<P>
Some proposals come from a single member of the CPPCC National
Committee, while some others were jointly submitted by more than
100 members, or even in the name of a party. Nevertheless, most of
the proposals originated from from experts and professors.
</P>
<P>
Member Gao Shipin noted that the reason the CPPCC could set
forth so many proposals is that the government respects the
democratic consultative system and is willing to accept and handle
the proposals. Moreover, the CPPCC members have a strong sense of
responsibility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
