<HEADLINE> Japan to Provide More Aid to Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Japan has decided to grant more aid
to Myanmar under the scheme of grass roots grant assistance,
according to a press release of the Japanese embassy here today.
</P>
<P>
The grant aid totaling 370,250 U.S. dollars is to be provided
for the projects of two hospitals in Yangon and two urban health
centers in Mandalay and Magway under the contracts signed here
today between Japanese ambassador Yoichi Yamaguchi and heads of
respective Myanmar departments.
</P>
<P>
Japan had earlier extended to Myanmar a total of 390,598
dollars for similar projects in the country during last month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Japan also extended to Myanmar a grant-in-aid of
four billion yen (about 33 million dollars) used for debt relief,
according to an earlier press release of the Japanese embassy here
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Japan, a major donor for Myanmar in the past, is also a major
creditor nation for Myanmar which is in debt of up to 400 billion
yen (about 3.3 billion dollars).  
</P>
