<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's state revenues fell 6 percent to 8.1
billion shekels (about 2.3 billion U.S. dollars) last month from
8.6 billion shekels (about 2.5 billion U.S. dollars) in January.
</P>
<P>
Today's Jerusalem Post said that over the last three months
state revenues dropped 0.7 percent in real terms to 25.3 billion
shekels (about 8 billion dollars) compared with the same period a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
These are the latest of a series of figures showing that the
Israeli Treasury is finding it consistently difficult to meet
its own revenue targets.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A German consortium led by Siemens Ltd. (Israel)
has won a tender to supply 9 million U.S. dollars of equipment
for the construction of the Gaza International Airport, today's
Jerusalem Post reported.
</P>
<P>
Siemens managing director Ekkehard Koethe said that the
potential political difficulties did not affect the consortium's
decision to bid for the tender.
</P>
<P>
The consortium will supply electrical and communication
technologies for use in the terminals and security systems.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Siemens said the Gaza Airport will be
operational by 1998, but Israel has not committed to a date.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's 12-month inflation rate has risen to 78.6
percent as a result of a 6.2 percent increase in wholesale prices
in February.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News today quoted figures released by
the State Institute of Statistics (DIE) as saying that the
12-month increase in wholesale prices was the highest since the
recorded 84.9 percent for the December 1995-December 1996.
</P>
<P>
While the wholesale prices rose by 6.2 percent in February,
the consumer prices went down 5.7 percent, according to
the DIE data.
</P>
<P>
The respective January increases in wholesale and consumer
prices were 5.6 and 5.9 percent respectively, it added.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Abdullatif Sener, however, said the country's
chronic high inflation was on a downward trend, explaining that
the annual interest rates had been lowered to around 80 percent
due to some appropriate and effective measures by the coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Premier Chemical Co., Cyprus' leading pesticides
manufacturer, has clinched a deal to supply pesticides worth 1
million U.S. dollars to Iraq, Financial Mirror reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the Cypriot company is now the fourth one
worldwide to win a contract for the supply of goods to the Iraqi
government under the U.N.-Iraqi oil-for-food deal signed last May.
</P>
<P>
Before the U.N. Security Council imposed sanctions on Iraq for
its invasion of Kuwait in 1990, Iraq used to buy goods worth 4
million dollars annually from this company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
