<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Project Proceeds Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- China's giant Three Gorges Project
is an ecology-friendly undertaking and construction of its first
phase is going slightly ahead of schedule with investment below
estimates, official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The project, the world's largest water conservancy undertaking
on the Yangtze River, China's longest, has both positive and
negative impacts on the environment, Guo Shuyan, vice minister in
charge of the State Planning Commission and deputy director of the
State Council Three Gorges Project Construction Committee, said at
a press conference organized by the Eighth People's National
Congress, China's legislature, which has been in session since
last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"But feasibility studies have shown that advantages overweigh
disadvantages in terms of the environment," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Project, with an estimated investment of 90
billion yuan at 1993 prices, or 203.4 billion yuan in dynamic
prices when it completes in 2009, will help replace otherwise
polluting energies used in affected areas with a pollution-free,
clean and renewable energy, Guo said.
</P>
<P>
The burning of coal to generate power causes pollution,
and coal shipment puts strains on the transportation system, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The project will also help reduce the threat of floods at the
middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze River, cutting the
incidence of serious floods to once in 100 years from once in ten
years, Guo said.
</P>
<P>
"The Three Gorges Project has a very important role to play in
flood control in the Yangtze River valley," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lu Youmei, General Manager of China Yangtze Three Gorges
Project Development Corp., said that construction of the project
will not affect navigation and will instead raise the river's
navigable tonnage by a big margin.
</P>
<P>
Despite all this, Guo admitted the project could produce
negative effects on animals and plants. Silting may also pose a
problem, he said.
</P>
<P>
"But with proper measures, we can solve or minimize the
problems," Guo said, adding that silting will unlikely pose a
serious problem to the project itself and, taking into
consideration of all factors, the storage capacity of the
reservoir will maintain at 86 percent of its designed capacity.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, the Three Gorges Project can be called an ecology
project... and it will make people there live and work in a safer
and better environment," he said.
</P>
<P>
On protection of cultural sites and relics in the project area,
Guo said that both the central government and local governments
are keen on it.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese central government and local governments have
organized dozens of geological surveys after the launching of the
project in 1993 and special funds have been earmarked for the
protection of sites and objects, he said, adding that finds
include one item of national level and 26 at the provincial
level.
</P>
<P>
He denied a lack of funding for protecting cultural sites and
objects, saying: "As we can afford the project, we can also afford
to protect the sites and objects."
</P>
<P>
He said that China looks forward to cooperating with other
countries with regard to the protection of sites of historical
interest and cultural relics in the project area, adding that
Canada and Japan have already expressed interest in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Guo said that to date a total of 19.1 billion yuan has been
invested in the project, including 5.97 billion yuan for
the resettlement of displaced residents.
</P>
<P>
He said that the first group of generators will begin
operational in 2003, with annual power generation expected to hit
84.7 billion kwh by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the gigantic project's first phase is slightly
ahead of schedule and investment in the phase is about four billion
yuan less than planned, Guo said.
</P>
<P>
To increase funding, the corporation has issued one billion
yuan in corporate bonds since February 28. Lu dismissed any plan
to issue bonds overseas in the near future.
</P>
<P>
He said that all debts will be repaid by the year 2012.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
