<HEADLINE> German Siemens Wins Gaza Airport Tender </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 5 (Xinhua) -- A German consortium led by
Siemens Ltd. (Israel) has won a tender to supply 9 million U.S.
dollars of equipment for the construction of the Gaza
International Airport, today's Jerusalem Post reported.
</P>
<P>
However, Israel has not yet given final approval for the
airport, a criterion that must be met before the Palestinians
can operate flights to and from the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Siemens managing director Ekkehard Koethe said that the
potential political difficulties did not affect the consortium's
decision to bid for the tender.
</P>
<P>
The consortium will supply electrical and communication
technologies for use in the terminals and security systems.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Siemens said the Gaza Airport will be
operational by 1998, but Israel has not committed to a date.
</P>
<P>
"The whole idea of the airport is in negotiations," said
Yigal Palmor, a Foreign Ministry spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, most of the airport's three-kilometer runway has
been built inside Palestinian controlled territory, and the
terminal, on which work has begun without Israeli permission, is
supposed to straddle the Israel-Palestinian Gaza border so
Israel can control the arrivals and departures of all
passengers.
</P>
<P>
"Business is business, and when we are asked to give an
offer, we place an offer. When we are awarded a contract we take
it," Koethe said. "We cannot say what the next steps will be and
if the project will be realized." 
</P>
</TEXT>
