<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Proposing Secret Talks With Syria: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Israel is proposing secret
talks with Syria in order to break the protracted deadlock on the
Israeli-Syrian track of the peace process, a newspaper report said
today.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting with visiting French Foreign Minister
Herve de Charette Tuesday, Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu reportedly asked him to convey a message to Syrian
President Hafez Assad that Israel is willing to hold secret
talks wherever the Syrians like.
</P>
<P>
"You can tell the Syrians that we will meet them in
Washington, Paris, or wherever they like. If they want to
meet secretly, this is fine, too," Netanyahu was quoted by
The Jerusalem Post as telling de Charette.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu urged the Syrians to abandon the view that he
was not serious about peace but only wanted to drag out
the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"Arabs said that when we were negotiating on Hebron that we
wanted the talks to drag, but they were wrong. We did a Hebron
deal," Netanyahu added.
</P>
<P>
During separate talks with de Charette, Israeli Foreign
Minister David Levy reportedly mentioned the possibility that, in
order to bridge the gap with Syria, Israel could agree that
the first issue on the agenda is to reach a definition of where
the talks left off a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian talks were suspended last March following a
series of suicide bombings in Israel. Although Israel's Likud
government, which came to power last June, has repeatedly called
for the resumption of the talks without preconditions, Syria has
rejected the calls, insisting the talks be only resumed from the
point where they left off a year ago.
</P>
<P>
It means that the talks should be resumed on the basis
of the informal understanding reached between Israel's former
Labor government and Syria, in which Israel pledged to
withdraw fully from the occupied Golan Heights in return for
Syria's agreement to sign a peace deal with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Likud government has vowed never to relinquish its
self-proclaimed sovereignty over the Golan Heights on grounds of
protecting the safety of its water resources and northern
border. Recently, Israeli officials have indicated the
willingness to agree to a partial withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
De Charette, whose country maintains good relations with
Syria, is to travel to Damascus tonight. France, seeking a
greater role in the peace process, is trying to bring the
two rivals back to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
But no breakthrough is expected from de Charette's current
mediation tour in view of the hardline message from Syria,
which was conveyed by him to Netanyahu during the Tuesday
meeting. Syria said that Damascus would not budge from
insistence that talks cannot resume unless they begin where
they left off a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The message was issued by Syrian Vice President Abdul Halim
Khaddam and Foreign Minister Farouk Shara, who visited Paris
last week to discuss the prospects of resuming the Israeli-Syrian
talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
