<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Races Toward Economic Globalization (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 5 (Xinhua) -- China's largest economic center
of Shanghai is increasing its global cooperation, as overseas
capital rushes in and more local companies choose to test the
waters in markets elsewhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
"Shanghai's economic contact with the rest of the world is
increasing, and the city is marching toward the great goal of
becoming an international economic, financial and trade center at
an unprecedented speed," a municipal government official said.
</P>
<P>
"One of Shanghai's priorities is to internationalize its
economy," the official told Xinhua News Agency, adding that the
city's comprehensive opening-up drive in recent years has had
successes in forging an overseas-oriented economy.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the influx of overseas capital, technology and
talent, the overseas-related sector's contribution to Shanghai's
economy has surged to 30 percent, a growth of 13 percent, or 287.7
billion yuan (about 34.6 billion U.S. dollars) since last year,
according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Annual contractual overseas investment in the city topped 10
billion US dollars for the third consecutive year in 1996 to hit
an all-time high of about 11.1 billion US dollars, with 7.51
billion US dollars actually used, up almost 42 percent from 1995.
</P>
<P>
Official data also showed that Shanghai had approved more than
15,000 overseas-funded projects by the end of last year,
attracting over 80.51 billion US dollars in contractual overseas
direct investment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Police Crack Down on Illegal Emigration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has always
opposed illegal emigration and police departments in Fujian, where
illegal emigration was once serious, have clamped down on "snake
heads," said a local government advisor today.
</P>
<P>
You Dexin, a member of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) National Committee, said the entry
into the United States of some illegal immigrants from China's
Fujian province resulted from the criminal activities of "snake
heads" based in China and the rest of the world and operating in
collusion with one another.
</P>
<P>
"They deceived Chinese citizens for money," said You, who is
also chairman of the Fujian Provincial Committee of the CPPCC, at
a press conference today organized by the ongoing session of the
CPPCC National Committee.
</P>
<P>
"Illegal emigration has caught the attention of the national
and Fujian provincial governments. Cracking down on illegal
emigration has been an important part of government work in
Changle and Lianjiang counties, where illegal emigration was most
serious," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
