<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Races Toward Economic Globalization (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Overseas investment has helped ease a capital shortage in
Shanghai's economic construction and generated an annual tax
revenue of nearly ten billion yuan," he said. "Moreover, it has
helped bring in advanced technology and management expertise."
</P>
<P>
The Pudong New Area, a de facto special economic zone and an
emerging economic and trade district separated from downtown
Shanghai by the Huangpu River, has become a leader in the city's
race to become a world economic center.
</P>
<P>
Rapid economic development and accelerated opening-up over the
past six years have turned the area into a favorite destination of
overseas investment, the official said, adding that as many as 63
multinationals have landed in the area, with overseas-funded firms
making up 35 percent of the area's gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
And while overseas capital, technology and managers are lured
to the city by its great economic prospects, over 400 companies in
Shanghai have ventured overseas, making handsome investments in
more than 50 countries and regions worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Zhenhua Port Machinery Co. Ltd, a Pudong-based
producer of cranes for handling containers, has successfully taken
its business to dozens of the world's leading ports and earned 80
million US dollars from exports last year.
</P>
<P>
Already the nation's biggest technology-intensive base for
manufacturing, processing industries and technological
development, Shanghai still seeks to tap its potential in
technology exports, which raked in 400 million US dollars last
year.
</P>
<P>
The city will also load its technology export information onto
the Internet later this year to boost the exporting business,
according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Closer ties with the rest of the world significantly hiked up
the city's foreign trade volume to 22.26 billion US dollars-worth
last year, up 16.8 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Opening yuan-based business to overseas banks in the Pudong New
Area, which was first sanctioned by the central bank late last
year as a major move to open the nation's financial sector, has
pushed Shanghai a substantial step closer toward the goal of going
global financially, experts said.
</P>
<P>
To date, eight overseas branch banks in China, including
Citibank of the United States, the Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking
Corp. and the Industrial Bank of Japan, have been given the
green light to deal in the Chinese currency, the Renminbi yuan.
</P>
<P>
A total of 193 overseas financial institutions had opened in
Shanghai by the end of last year, with their assets valued well
over 13.5 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Observers maintain that all aspects of Shanghai's growing
economic exchange with other parts of the world as well as its
past glory as an economic and financial haven in the Far East are
combining to add more international clout to its economy.
</P>
<P>
"The economic globalization of Shanghai is something that is
already riding on a fast track," one analyst said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tightens International Co-op in Wetlands Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIDAIHE, March 5 (Xinhua) -- China will enhance its
international cooperation in protecting and reasonably utilizing
the country's wetlands, said a Chinese official, who is attending
an international symposium on wetlands and water birds protection.
</P>
<P>
China will cooperate with the International Wetlands
Organization to evaluate, monitor, and manage the country's
wetlands and make relevant policies, the official said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the symposium, which followed the establishment of
China's office of the International Wetlands Organization, shows
that the Chinese government is making further progress in
protecting wetlands.
</P>
<P>
The office, set up in Beijing, will help China to make contact
with other countries and organizations, work out the plan for
wetlands protection and apply for international aid, said Chen
Kelin, who heads the office.
</P>
<P>
Wetlands are a kind of ecosystem, including lakes and
marshlands, with ecological and economic functions such as storing
floodwater for use against drought.
</P>
<P>
China now has 63 million hectares of various kinds of wetlands,
or 6.6 percent of the national total area and ranking first in
Asia, among which some have been listed as "Wetlands of
International Importance."
</P>
<P>
The symposium, which is held in Beidaihe, a sea-side resort in
north China's Hebei Province, is jointly sponsored by the Chinese
Ministry of Forestry, the Japan's Environmental Agency and the
Asia-Pacific Branch of the Wetlands International.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Biggest Industrial City Deepening Reforms of State Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
industrial city, is moving quickly to deepen reforms in its
state-owned firms and has made remarkable headway in creating a
modern enterprise system.
</P>
<P>
Trial reforms aimed at instituting the system in unprofitable
plants are in place in 250 state-owned firms, which account for 80
percent of the city's total state assets, according to officials
from the municipal economic and trade commission.
</P>
<P>
The modern enterprise system, an option developed by the
central government to pull money-losing firms out of difficulty,
separates the functions of government and businesses, and gives
more leeway to the managers of the firms rather than the
supervisors.
</P>
<P>
Of the 250 large businesses that are implementing the modern
enterprise system on an experimental basis, 120 have restructured
their management plans and are now prepared to enliven their
assets and optimize operations.
</P>
<P>
So far, Shanghai has turned 18 bureaus overseeing state-owned
firms into state-owned shareholding companies or large enterprise
groups.
</P>
<P>
With pillar industries, brand products and well-to-do firms
leading the way, Shanghai has set up quite a few big enterprise
groups through mergers and buy-outs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the city is speeding up the reorganization of its
small enterprises, while shifting the responsibility of 231 such
firms to districts and counties. Fifty-nine firms that
were no longer competitive on the market have been merged, while
43 unprofitable companies have gone bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
The move has helped bring the debt rate of small state-owned
industrial firms down from 80 percent in 1994 to 67 percent in
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
