<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Orders Closure of PNA Offices in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 5 (Xinhua) -- In a move that will fuel the
dispute over eastern Jerusalem, Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu has ordered the closure of four offices run by the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) in the city.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu gave the order late Tuesday night to Public
Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani, who will serve the letters
of closure today. The decision on the closure was reportedly
based on the recommendation of anti-terrorism chief Meir Dagan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after meeting with visiting presidents of major
U.S. Jewish organizations late Tuesday night, Netanyahu
reiterated that Israel had the sovereign rights over its
self-declared capital of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"We have consistent reports that I received from various
security agencies about the extent of the PNA violations (of the
Oslo accords) in Jerusalem. Under the Oslo, they commit
themselves to not having governmental institutions in Jerusalem
or PNA governmental activities," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are not asking them to shut them down, we are shutting
them down," Netanyahu stressed.
</P>
<P>
Kahalani today will hold consultations with Jerusalem police
on the closures and issued the letters to notify the concerned
PNA offices in the first stage. He warned that if the PNA refused
to cooperate, the police would take necessary steps which he did
not elaborate, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The radio report said, however, that the police were unlikely
to shut down the PNA offices now because of the possibility of
appealing to the High Court of Justice by the PNA.
</P>
<P>
So far the names of the targeted offices have not been
released, but a statement issued by the Prime Minister's Office
said that the security apparatus run by PNA security head Jibril
Rajoub would be expelled from eastern Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The decision to close the PNA offices was take on the eve of
Netanyahu's visit to Egypt today and at a time when Israel came
under increasing international criticism of its plan to build
Jewish settlement in Har Homa in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
This move is expected to fuel the already high tension
between Israel and the PNA. But Netanyahu's aides sharply denied
that the timing of the closures was political, rather they
insisted it was bureaucratic.
</P>
<P>
"I want to make clear that the closure of the offices has
nothing to do with Har Homa, nothing to do with the visit to
Egypt, and nothing to do with the upcoming further
redeployments," Netanyahu's media adviser David Bar-Illan was
quoted by The Jerusalem Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
The move also came as Netanyahu is seeking to galvanize a
majority for a pullback in the West Bank at the Thursday's
cabinet meeting. Under the Hebron agreement, Israel should
complete the first stage of the three-phase redeployments in the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that Netanyahu is seeking to widen the scope
of further troop pullouts in the West Bank in order to silence
the Palestinian protests over the Har Homa project and the
closure of PNA offices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
