<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Continues to Fall in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' year-on-year
inflation dropped to 4.4 percent in February this year compared
with five percent in January as prices of most commodities in the
country fell during that month, the National Statistics Office
said today.
</P>
<P>
The statistics office said in a report that on a month-on-month
basis, consumer prices continued to drop and stood at 0.4 percent
in February as compared with 0.6 percent in January and 0.8
percent last December.
</P>
<P>
"Prices of all the major commodity groups slowed down except in
the housing and repairs index which went up by 0.4 percentage
point to 9.6 percent from 9.2 percent in January," it said.
</P>
<P>
However, the inflation rate in Metro Manila was recorded at 6.6
percent in February and 6.1 percent in January, the office said.
</P>
<P>
The latest inflation data indicates that consumer price
increases this year could be boxed into the government's target of
six to 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the country's inflation was recorded at 8.4 percent,
just within the government's target of 7.5-8.5 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
