<HEADLINE> Mobile Police Unit Set up in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan police have set up a
Mobile Unit equipped with modern weapons to combat escalating
crimes like armed robberies in the country, the Daily Nation
paper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The new unit will use specially designed Land Rovers and act
as a special rapid deployment force to preempt car thefts, bank
robberies and other crimes.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-eight new police vehicles will be fully equipped with
modern weapons and communication facilities to enable policemen
to swiftly respond to armed robberies in the eastern African
country, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, five gangsters, three of them in police uniforms,
raided Trust Bank in the port city of Mombasa and grab about
240,000 Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, about 1.7 million U.S. Dollars were robbed by
gunmen at a branch of the Standard Chartered Bank in the capital
city of Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, about one million Dollars was casually stolen from
the Embakasi strongroom of Kenya Handling Ltd.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Police Commissioner Duncan Wachira as saying
on Tuesday that the Police Mobile Unit will be deployed in
Nairobi, Mombasa, Kisumu, Nakuru, Eldoret, Kiambu and Thika, and
in bandit-prone areas to help combating cattle-rustling.
</P>
<P>
Wachira noted that as criminals have become sophisticated and
have acquired faster and more powerful cars, the policemen need
better vehicles to cope with the criminals.
</P>
<P>
He said that the purchase of the vehicles by the government
was a first step toward ensuring the total security for everyone
in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
