<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Selected Librettos Collected by Qing Prince Brought To Light </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Librettos selected from a
collection of a prince of the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) have been
published by the Beijing Ancient Books Publishing House.
</P>
<P>
The collection, most of which has never been published before,
consists of 1,585 pieces of hand-written works, falling into two
categories -- librettos and verses for singing.
</P>
<P>
The newly published selection, which comprises two-thirds of
the collection, is divided into 1,100 columns in 200 boxes.
</P>
<P>
Photomechanically printed on Xuan paper, a high quality paper
made in Xuancheng, Anhui Province especially prized for
traditional Chinese paintings and calligraphy, the selections are
packaged in boxes wrapped in Song (960-1279) style embroideries.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts say that the selection rivals, in terms of
academic significance, the canon of Tang (618-907) poetry and the
works of Song Ci, in which poetry written to certain tunes with
strict tonal patterns and rhyme schemes, and fixed numbers of
lines and words, was fully developed in the Song Dynasty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Famine Threatens Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Famine looms in 19 of Uganda's 39
districts and the government has sent a SOS message to relevant
donors, a high-ranking official has said.
</P>
<P>
Paul Etyang, the third deputy prime minister and the minister
of labor and social affairs, said in a statement in Parliament
that 2.1 million Ugandans are likely to be affected.
</P>
<P>
The Uganda government has called on World Food Program (WFP),
U.N. Children's Fund (UNICEF), U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) and the International Committee of Red Cross for
urgent assistance, The New Vision daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The government has taken precaution measures against
starvation, Etyang was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He blamed famine on rebellion in the north and in Kasese
district in the west, indiscriminate sale of food after harvest
in the east and ecological factors.
</P>
<P>
Among the 19 famine-harassed districts are Apac, Gulu, Kitgum
districts in the north, Soroti, Kumi, Moroto, Pallisa, Mbale
districts in the east, Mukono, Rakai districts in the central and
Maindi, Kabale, Kabarole and Kisoro districts in the west.
</P>
<P>
District disaster committees have been established, but their
operation are being constrained due to lack of sufficient funds,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government has so far allocated 284 million of
Uganda Shillings (some 284,000 U.S. Dollars) from its treasury to
ease the famine, Etyang told the parliament session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
