<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Allow Foreign Residents to Deal Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 5 (Xinhua) -- A comprehensive study has been
completed in Kuwait to allow foreign residents to deal in stocks
and shares in the small desert country, according to local press
reports today.
</P>
<P>
An announcement by Kuwait's Ministry of Commerce and Industry,
published today in Kuwaiti newspapers, said that the ministry
recently completed a study permitting expatriates residing in
Kuwait to buy and sell Kuwaiti shares.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti bourse has 47 banks and companies with a
market capitalization of around 10 billion U.S. dollars. Before
1990, there were 54 institutions with a capitalization of 12
billion U.S. dollars and the market was the busiest in the
Middle East due to widespread speculation.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait shut the door for foreign investors just after its
liberation from Iraqi occupation in 1991, and it re-opened the
door for citizens of the other five Gulf Cooperation Council
countries -- Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Oman, Bahrain
 and Qatar in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Kuwait signed a pact on a joint formula to link its
stock exchange market with those of Bahrain and Oman to allow
each other to register limited liability companies in any of the
three markets and encourage investment among them.
</P>
<P>
Trading in the Kuwaiti Stock Exchange Market has been very
active since last year.
</P>
<P>
The expected re-opening of Kuwaiti bourse to foreigners other
than only GCC citizens would attract foreign investors and
stop the flow of capital from the country by encouraging
expatriate workers to send less money home, observers here
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
