<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to See New Gem-testing Technique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is expected to have a new
testing technique to separate synthetic amethysts from natural
ones, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The new testing technology, which was developed by a laboratory
at the Asian Institute of Gemmological Sciences, will
significantly help the country screen those fakes on the market in
this category of gemstone, the Bangkok Post said.
</P>
<P>
However, the lab did not disclose the details of the technique
as it worried about that producers of synthetic amethysts would
improve their own techniques to foil the new method.
</P>
<P>
During the trial testing period starting last November, the lab
tested a large number of amethyst parcels and did find a single
parcel with 100 percent natural amethysts, the lab management
said.
</P>
<P>
In some parcels, 60 percent were found as synthetics, while
stones in some other parcels were all synthetic, they said.
</P>
<P>
The practice of mixing synthetic gemstones with natural ones
has been widespread on the market, the newspaper said, adding that
the new method with high accuracy will greatly help curb this
practice.
</P>
<P>
The lab currently is expanding the scope of this testing
method. The cost for testing is about 25 baht (about 1 U.S.
dollars) per stone for bulk orders and 60 to 70 baht (about 2.4 to
2.8 dollars) per stone for a single stone.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Precious, Ancient Stone Tablet Copied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, March 5 (Xinhua) -- A stone tablet from the Tang Dynasty
(618-907), appraised as a national treasure, has been copied in
China's northwest Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The tablet, built according to imperial verdict, bears
inscriptions of an article written by Wei Zheng, a prominent
minister in the early days of the Tang Dynasty, and handwriting by
Ouyang Xun, one of the most famous calligraphers in Chinese
history.
</P>
<P>
Carved by top craftsmen of the dynasty, the tablet with
inscriptions on Liquan (wine spring) in Jiucheng Palace in Linyou
County, was called "the best example of regular script".
</P>
<P>
Over the past centuries, however, the tablet was seriously damaged
by outdoor exhibition and frequent rubbings in subsequent dynasties.
</P>
<P>
Nineteen characters of the 1,108-character inscription were
missing, 39 characters incomplete, while another 180 characters
have blurred. The entire tablet has lost much of its original
look.
</P>
<P>
To restore the original look of the tablet, Ren Buwu, a
64-year-old calligrapher in Shaanxi, decided to copy the
inscription with support from Chinese archaeological and
calligraphical communities.
</P>
<P>
With a rubbing from the early Song Dynasty (960-1279) as his
model, the earliest of its kind in existence, Ren consulted
six other inscriptions by Ouyang Xun and some 200 stone tablets
from the Northern Wei Dynasty (386-534) to repair the 238 missing,
incomplete or blurred characters.
</P>
<P>
It took two years for Ren to study the characters and more than
another year for him and several famous craftsmen to write and
carve the article on a piece of shallow grey marble.
</P>
<P>
The new tablet is 210 cm high, 35 cm over the original, 110 cm
wide, 15-25 cm wider than the original, with a 110 cm cap, 20 cm
higher than the original cap.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts, who gathered here recently to assess the new
tablet, spoke highly of Ren's work, saying that it has recreated
much of Ouyang Xun's style, and has been a great essay in carrying
on traditional calligraphy.
</P>
<P>
The new tablet is now collected in the Museum of Baoji City.
</P>
<P>
The original, having been covered by a kiosk in Linyou county
in Baoji, has attracted hundreds of thousands of tourists from
both home and abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
