<HEADLINE> Israel Proposes to Turkey to Modernize Tanks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Israel has made a proposal for
Turkey to modernize its aged M-60 tanks, local newspaper Daily
News reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli proposal was officially made early this year
and envisages the modernization of about 300 U.S.-made M-60
tanks in a program to be carried out both in Turkey and
Israel, the paper quoted a Turkish defense source as saying.
</P>
<P>
The source said that Turkish and Israeli sides have not
discussed the cost and length of the program.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli offer foresees the modernization of the Turkish
Ground Forces' M-60 tanks which remain outdated with their
1960s technology, and Israeli experts also proposed to modernize
the first tank free of charge as a test case," said the
source.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkey is to produce at least 1,000 third
generation tanks in a 4.5-billion-U.S.-dollar project to meet the
defense needs of the army's 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel have signed two agreements on military
training and defense industry cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The military training agreement, signed in February 1996,
sparked a quarrel in Mideast countries as they believed that
Turkey was aligning itself with Israel against the interests of
Arab countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
