<HEADLINE> Israel's State Revenues Fall 6 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Israel's state revenues fell 6
percent to 8.1 billion shekels (about 2.3 billion U.S. dollars)
last month from 8.6 billion shekels (about 2.5 billion
U.S. dollars) in January.
</P>
<P>
Today's Jerusalem Post said that over the last three months
state revenues dropped 0.7 percent in real terms to 25.3 billion
shekels (about 8 billion dollars) compared with the same period a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
These are the latest of a series of figures showing that the
Israeli Treasury is finding it consistently difficult to meet
its own revenue targets.
</P>
<P>
The treasury placed much of the blame of last year's
large budget deficit, and subsequent need for the budget cut,
on the failure to collect revenues according to the
projections formulated last summer.
</P>
<P>
This continued failure could result in a further budget cut
of up to 2 billion shekels (some 650 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Israeli Finance Minister Dan Meridor has repeatedly said he
will not countenance further cuts until he has digested all
the budgetary data for the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Finance Ministry could face an annual
shortfall of 3 billion to 3.5 billion shekels (around one billion
dollars), according to initial forecasts by economists.
</P>
<P>
However, senior treasury officials are dismissing these figures
as exaggerated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
