<HEADLINE> Mine-Shaft Prisons Under Consideration: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Overcrowding in prison has
promoted South African security authorities to consider turning
disused mine shafts into "maximum security prisons", the Citizen
daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to Department of Correctional Services Commissioner
Khulekani Sithole, there are more than 124,000 inmates in South
African jails, which are designed for only 97,000.
</P>
<P>
The proposal to put prisoners into mine-shafts is aimed at
alleviating overcrowding in jails in the country, Sithole said.
</P>
<P>
Another reason for the idea of underground prisons is to
prevent increasing escapees, he said.
</P>
<P>
Department of Correctional Services spokesman Rudi Potgieter
said yesterday that the idea of using disused mines also included
making use of existing infrastructures, such as old mine
buildings.
</P>
<P>
However, Potgieter said details on what "super maximum
security prisons" would entail were sketchy at present as the
idea needed thorough investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
