<HEADLINE> China Initiating Interprovincial Grain Reserve Transfer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, MARCH 5 (Xinhua) -- When the train from northeast
China, fully loaded with maize, arrived in southwest China a few
days later, the interprovincial grain reserve transfer began.
</P>
<P>
China reaped a record harvest in 1996. Total grain output
reached 480 billion kilograms. Northeast China's Jilin Province, a
major grain production base, yielded 23.2 billion kilograms of
grain, 2.5 billion kilograms beyond their capacity to stock.
</P>
<P>
To ease the storage pressure, the State Council initiated the
large-scale transfer to equalize distribution of grain reserves
and stabilize the grain market.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of 1.5 million tons of maize from Jilin is to
be transported to the most populous Sichuan Province, southwest of
China. More will be shipped out of the three northeastern
provinces and the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
All concerned provinces and ministries give the transfer the
green light. The Jilin Province loses no time drying grains of
high moisture content, and the Railway Ministry arranges carriages
while the Bank of Agricultural Development ensures capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
