<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Declares Friday Jerusalem Defense Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) has declared Friday as "the Defense of Jerusalem
Day," in a series of protests against Israel's decision to build
a new Jewish neighborhood in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
PNA called on Palestinian residents in the West Bank to attend
a prayer service at the Har Homa (Jabal Abu Ghneim), in the
southeastern outskirts of Jerusalem, where the new Jewish
neighborhood is planned to be built, Israel Radio reported this
morning.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last week, the Israeli government approved the plan to
build 6,500 Jewish homes in Har Homa, of which 2,450 will be
completed in the first three years.
</P>
<P>
In parallel, the government said it would start to build
3,015 units for Palestinians in 10 existing neighborhoods within
the city limits.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials reacted angrily to the building plan,
saying the Israeli government's decision is a violation of law
and its agreements with the Palestinians, and has put the
peace process in danger.
</P>
<P>
PNA President Yasser Arafat, who is currently visiting the
United States, has said that the Israeli government's decision
to go ahead with the construction of Har Homa presented a
"real challenge" to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is due to brief the United Nations Security Council
today shortly before the council, requested by the PNA and
other Arab countries, starts to debate the Har Homa issue.
</P>
<P>
Later in the weekend, the PNA president is also expected
to participate in a massive rally in the Gaza Strip to
protest against the building of Har Homa.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian organizers told Israel Radio that the protests by
the Palestinian people will be "no-violent."
</P>
<P>
However, a senior Israeli police officer warned that if the
construction of Har Homa begins, the Palestinians will response
with rioting on a scale similar to that after the opening
of the Western Wall Tunnel last September.
</P>
<P>
During a violent confrontation between Palestinian police and
Israeli soldiers, triggered off by the opening of the tunnel
by Israel in Jerusalem's Old City, more than 70 people were
killed and hundreds of others wounded.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Har Homa construction, scheduled to start
Tuesday, has been postponed due "technical reasons," but Israel
Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu stressed that Israel will
carry out the project soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
