<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Desert Turns into Tibet's Warehouse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Golmud, a city built 34 years ago on
a sparsely-populated desert, has become the largest warehouse for
southwest China's Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
So far, Golmud in Qinghai Province has set up more than 50
bases in Tibet, providing commercial goods, petroleum, grain,
medicine and farm machinery to the remote Himalayan region. Tibet
also invested more than 30 million yuan in setting up processing
enterprises in Golmud.
</P>
<P>
In 1953, China built the Qinghai-Tibet highway with an
elevation of 4,500 meters, the highest in the world.
</P>
<P>
With the constant improvement of the highway and the expansion
of links between Tibet and other parts of China, Golmud, which is
about 800 km from the provincial capital of Xining, has not only
become the second largest city in Qinghai, but also a storehouse
for goods for Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 44 years, China has transported 15 million tons
of goods from the landlocked area to Tibet, and large amount of
animal products, minerals, medicine and timber from Tibet back to
the inland.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislators, Advisors Call for More Educational Input </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese legislators and government
advisors today called for increasing financial input in education.
</P>
<P>
Wang Hu, a noted educationist, appreciated the government for
its efforts to increase its investment in education and but said
that the key to increasing input lies in the maintenance of its
status as the chief investor in education.
</P>
<P>
Laws should be strictly enforced and efforts be made to
guarantee that the proportion of educational investment to
finances at all levels rises along with the growth of the national
economy, he added.
</P>
<P>
"This is stipulated in the Education Law," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wang has submitted a proposal in this regard along with 30
other members of the National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), the country's top
advisory body that is in its fifth session here.
</P>
<P>
Chen Xiuli, a deputy to the National People's Congress, said an
prevalent problem is that some local officials have failed to
recognize the strategic importance of developing education, noting
that some financial allocations for education have been increased
and channels of collecting funds for education needs to be
diversified.
</P>
<P>
"To grasp Comrade Deng Xiaoping's thinking of revitalizing the
country through science and technology is still the No.1 task of
officials at various levels," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Many deputies and members held that educational funds can be
raised through a combination of various channel since the state
treasury is financial strained.
</P>
<P>
NPC Deputy Xu Jialu said that the on-going efforts to merge
financially-weak institutions of higher learning will help amass
limited funds and materials.
</P>
<P>
"Our focus should shift to quality and efficiency," he said.
</P>
<P>
Professor Qi Kang said inadequate funding for education has
something to do with a lack of scientific planning.
</P>
<P>
However, CPPCC National Committee Member Liang Zhiwen said: "If
the state-owned enterprises become more efficient, funding for
education won't be a problem."
</P>
<P>
Qu Shijing of the Shanghai Academy of Social Sciences, urged
the authorities to improve the structure of educational input.
</P>
<P>
The per-capita educational funding for middle and primary
school students is about 4.7 and 1.8 percent of the average for
students at higher learning institutions, he said, noting that the
figure in other countries stands at more than 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
"This is a reason that China's primary education is large in
size but poor is efficiency," Qu said.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of China's public educational funding to the
gross domestic product reached 3.3 percent in 1980 and 3.6 percent
in 1985. At present, the figure is just over two percent, lower
than the average for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
As the national economy grows, China can increase the figure to
four percent, as stipulated in a program for the country's
educational reform and development, Wang Hu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
