<HEADLINE> Expanding Scientific Cooperations Benefit Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin, a major port city in
north China, has benefited greatly from its increasing cooperation
with foreign countries in science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 150 million US dollars-worth of cooperative
agreements were signed.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that nearly 1,000 foreign experts came to China
in 1996 to work in the fields of machinery, electronics, textiles,
agriculture, environmental protection and infrastructure
construction.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, some 30 Japanese experts have been in the
municipality, while 17 Chinese scientific researchers were sent to
Japan in accordance with a cooperative program between the two
sides. And more than 50 academic papers have been published.
</P>
<P>
Officials in Tianjin said that under the guidance of Canadian
experts, scientific methods have been put to use in local
chicken-raising farms, which help to lower the chickens' mortality
rate and raise the rate of egg-laying.
</P>
<P>
The sector reported an increase of nearly one million US
dollars in earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
