<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya sells 5 Parastatal Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
approved the sale of five parastatal companies under the on-going
privatization program, the Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted George Mitine, Investment Secretary of the
Parastatal Reform Program Committee, as saying that the committee
had proved the sale of government shares of five firms.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Tourism Development Corporation shares in the Sunset
Hotel was sold to Piedmont Investment Ltd. at a price of about 20
million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The committee approved the sale of 550,000 shares owned by the
government in Kenya National Properties to the ICDC Investment
Company at an offer price of four Dollars a share through
preemptive rights.
</P>
<P>
The government shares were also sold in Dawa Pharmaceuticals,
Safari Lodges and Properties, and Polysynthetic E.A.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that a second disbursement of 37 million
Dollars from the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to Kenya under
a soft-loan program has been delayed for three months because of
what the fund sees as slow progress on privatization.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Kenya agreed on a 220 million Dollars aid plan
under the IMF soft-loan Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility.
</P>
<P>
The first disbursement of 37 million Dollars was issued early
last year and the second one was due in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
An IMF official was quoted as saying that "what we want is to
avoid budgetary funds being used to help out ailing parastatals."
</P>
</TEXT>
