<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Seek 610 Million Dollars Loan From Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will seek some 610
million U.S. dollars from Japan at a consultation meeting which
began here today to discuss new development projects under
Japanese aid, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
An eight-member Japanese consultation mission on official
development assistance loans is attending in the two-day meeting,
which took place after a lapse of two years due to political
unrest in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The new government of Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina would place
eight projects, mainly in infrastructure and power sectors, with a
total involvement of 928 million U.S. dollars, and ask for 610
million dollars from the Japanese government, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
The projects to be placed at the meeting include the Jamuna
bridge access road project, the Paksey bridge project, four power
sector projects, an irrigation project and a port development
project, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
Japan, one of the largest bilateral donors for Bangladesh,
offers an average of 200 million U.S. dollars annually to this
poor South Asian country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
