<HEADLINE> Stanchart Profits in Africa Marks 49 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The profits of Standard and
Chartered Plc marked a 49 percent increaset in Africa to 64 million
Pounds Sterling in the year 1996.
</P>
<P>
A statement of the bank group quoted by today's ''Times of
Zambia'' said that the year 1996 saw strong asset growth in local
currency terms in all the major countries of Zambia, Kenya,
Zimbabwe, Botswana and Ghana.
</P>
<P>
The total pre-tax profit of the bank group was a record of 870
million Pounds Sterling, an increase of 32 percent for the year
ended December 1996.
</P>
<P>
Group chief executive Malcolm Williamson attributed the
achievement by growing net revenue and tight control of operation
costs.
</P>
<P>
Williamson said that the group's strategy remains to develop
the strong franchises in Asia, the Middle East and Africa, using
operations in Europe and the Americas as a bridge to those
markets.
</P>
<P>
''Our business focus is on personal banking and consumer
finance, on corporate and institutional banking with special
emphasis on trade and cash management, on custody and treasury
and on certain defined investment banking services,'' Williamson
noted.
</P>
<P>
He added, ''these are all areas where we have strength and
expertise. We have disposed of most of those parts of the group
which did not fit this strategy.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
