<HEADLINE> Jiangxi Striving for Tourism Boom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, March 5 (Xinhua) -- In the spirit of the national "Visit
China '97" tourism campaign, East China's Jiangxi Province expects
an economic boost as tourists arrive in record numbers.
</P>
<P>
With the speed of trains on the Beijing-Kowloon Railway Line, a
major transport artery which passes through Jiangxi, being raised
to normal standards, train travelers are bound to increase,
according to local government officials.
</P>
<P>
The best-known summer resort of the Lushan Mountain, Jiangxi's
famous tourist attraction, has been designated as a world-class
natural heritage, while the Jinggang Mountains will celebrate the
70th anniversary of the establishment of its well-known
revolutionary base, they added.
</P>
<P>
By taking advantage of these opportunities, the province
has launched a series of tourist events, such as the Lushan
International Tourism Festival, the Taoist Culture Festival at
Longhu Mountain, and an Plum Blossom Appreciation Festival.
</P>
<P>
More than 70 percent of the tourism resources in the province
have joined hands with other major tourist cities such as Beijing
and Guangdong to lure overseas tourists.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Jiangxi played host to nearly 100,000
overseas visitors last year, up 34.5 percent from 1995, with
tourism earnings reaching nearly 34 million US dollars in hard
currency.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of domestic tourists to the province
reached a record 13.1 million and earnings from services to such
tourists came to 4.73 billion yuan in 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
