<HEADLINE> Chinese Deputies Call for Enhanced History Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese legislators today called
for increasing Chinese history education among primary and middle
school students to promote socialist ethical and cultural
progress.
</P>
<P>
Ren Jiyu, director of Beijing Library, China's national
library, has forwarded a proposal in this regard to the Eighth
National People's Congress, the country's legislature, that has
been in session since last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese history provides a data bank for promoting ethical
and cultural progress, is an adhesive for unifying the 1.2 billion
people and contains seeds for cultivating patriotism," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If you do not know the dynasties of Xia, Shang and Zhou, the
Opium War, Sun Yat-sen or Japanese aggression against China, you
are not a qualified Chinese," he said.
</P>
<P>
Xia is believed to be the first dynasty in Chinese history,
which span the 21th-16th centuries B.C., followed by Shang (about
16th-11th centuries B.C.) and Zhou (about 11th century B.C.-221
B.C.).
</P>
<P>
"Ideological and moral education based on history will be
more lifelike and will increase people's patriotism," Ren said.
</P>
<P>
Feng Xianzhi, director of Party Literature Research Center of
the CPC Central Committee, said that the promotion of ethical and
cultural progress should be started in kindergartens and primary
schools.
</P>
<P>
"Schools are not only places where knowledge is disseminated,
but also important places for moral education," he said, adding
that such education should be carried out through primary schools,
middle schools and institutions of higher learning.
</P>
<P>
Kuang Peizi, a research fellow of the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, said that China's basic education should focus more on
students' overall qualities and moral standards.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Zhongli, president of the Shanghai Academy of Social
Sciences, said that China's ongoing effort to promote ethical
and cultural progress is not a short-term act.
</P>
<P>
He also proposed legislation for the promotion of ethical and
cultural progress.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
