<HEADLINE> IBM to Make Parts for Hard Disk Drive in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, March 5 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-US joint venture to
produce parts for hard disk drives, has been set up in Shenzhen in
south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
At a cost of 42.5 million US dollars, the Shenzhen Hailiang
Storage Products Co. Ltd., was jointly funded by IBM of the United
States and two local companies. IBM funded 80 percent of the joint
venture.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture, the largest one funded by IBM in China,
expects to annually provide 36 million magnetoresistive head
gimbal assemblies for hard disk drive assemblers worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Sharing a common goal to help promote hi-tech development in
China, IBM set up its first joint venture with the two partners in
Shenzhen in 1995. 
