<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan Health Care Improved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The average life expectancy has
more than doubled since 1949 in Hainan Province, China's largest
special economic zone.
</P>
<P>
Due to the improved health care in the province, the average
life expectancy now reached 73 years old, above the national
average, as opposed to 35 years old before the founding of new
China.
</P>
<P>
Located in the tropical area with a hot and rainy weather,
Hainan Island previously had been a breeding ground for infectious
diseases. In 1987, the incidence of such diseases was double the
national average.
</P>
<P>
Since Hainan Province became China's special economic zone, the
local government made a point of listing medical work in its plan
for economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, the province had 1,712 medical
organizations, more than 30,000 medical workers (about four for
every 1,000 people) and more than 20,000 beds in hospitals (about
three for every 1,000 people).
</P>
<P>
Rural medical work and the prevention and cure of infectious
diseases had been major tasks for medical care throughout the 1991-
1996 period.
</P>
<P>
By last year, some 128 million yuan (15.2 million US dollars) of
special funds were injected into the rural medical system. And 4,494
medical workers with college education, employed by the rural
medical organizations, significantly improved the quality of care.
</P>
<P>
The local government educated people to develop better hygiene,
and some fatal infectious diseases were wiped out.
</P>
<P>
The province has basically eliminated the incidence of
filariasis, and no cases of dengue fever were reported in the past
four years. No cases of wild strain polio have been reported in
the last three years.
</P>
<P>
After 1992, the province set up a medical system allowing for
various kinds of ownership to complement the state-owned
hospitals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0231 </DOCNO>
