<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Peace Mission in Bosnia to End On Time: U.S. Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen
said here today that in any case the NATO peace operation in
Bosnia will end on time in June of 1998 as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
After talking with his German counterpart Volker Ruehe, Cohen
told reporters that U.S. troops will leave Balkan at the end of
the peacekeeping mission in June next year.
</P>
<P>
"If we retreat from Bosnia after 16 months, the NATO forces
will also leave," he added.
</P>
<P>
Ruehe noted on the occasion that Germany will withdraw its
troops from Bosnia following the retreat of the U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
The United States has about 7,900 troops in Bosnia and Croatia
as part of the 30,000-strong allied peacekeeping forces. Germany
has contributed 3,000 to the mission.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ruehe called for maintaining peace and establishing
stronger balance of power among former warring sides in Bosnia in
the next 16 months.
</P>
<P>
Cohen, on his first trip abroad as Pentagon chief, also talked
with Ruehe on the issues of NATO's eastern expansion, strategic
partnership between NATO and Russia, the future frame of NATO, the
differences between the U.S. and France on the command of the
allied troops in southern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Both Cohen and Ruehe showed optimism on removing Russia's worry
about NATO's eastern expansion.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said that it is possible for NATO and Russia to sign a
specific charter on the expansion issue.
</P>
<P>
However, it is impossible for Russia to have the veto right
on NATO's internal affairs, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ruehe disclosed that a proposal would be raised at
the upcoming NATO summit in Madrid on accepting Hungary, the Czech
Republic and Poland as NATO members.
</P>
<P>
On U.S.-France differences, Cohen reiterated U.S. refusal to
allow France to command the allied troops in southern Europe. But
Ruehe hoped to find a way of compromise.
</P>
<P>
Ruehe said that in any case, the U.S. should be in the leading
position in the headquarters in the next few years, but an
European should act as aide of the top commander with clear-cut
power scope.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need to increase the number of European
officers in the headquarters.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral cooperations, Cohen termed Germany as "the most
important partner" to the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Ruehe pointed out that there is a big decrease in the number of
U.S. troops stationed in Europe from 320,000 seven years ago to
100,000 now.
</P>
<P>
Germany has become the largest foreign investor of the U.S.
since 1995, he said, adding that both Germany and the U.S. have
invested 15 billion U.S. dollars in each other's market.
</P>
<P>
He held out hope that cooperation between the two countries
will be furthered in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
