<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Situation in Albania Worsens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- All regions in Albania today set up
contingent commissions headed by their state governors to exercise
local authority under an order of the Albanian State Defense
Committee.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two days, Tirana and its surrounding areas
appeared calm but several towns in the south, including Vlore and
Sarande, were reportedly out of control.
</P>
<P>
It has been officially confirmed that Chief of the General
Staff of the Albanian National Army Sheme Kosova has been sacked
and replaced by General Adem Cobani, a military advisor to
President Sali Berisha.
</P>
<P>
President Berisha today rejected an opposition call for a
broad-based government to end the country's bloody unrest.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read on state television, Berisha accused the
opposition Socialist Party of organizing "armed rebellion" in the
south of the Balkan state.
</P>
<P>
"You decided to overturn the constitutional order and Albanian
democracy through an armed rebellion and created a grave problem
for the country," Berisha said in the statement issued after his
meeting with Socialist leaders, who called on Berisha to establish
a broad-based government to help end the crisis in the nation.
</P>
<P>
"I am against a coalition between the Democratic Party and the
Socialist Party," said Berisha, who was re-elected to a second
five-year term Monday by the Albanian parliament, where his
Democrats hold virtually all the seats.
</P>
<P>
The Socialists, the biggest force in an 11-party opposition
Forum for Democracy, bluntly denied Berisha's allegations that
they have orchestrated the unrest caused by the collapse of
popular, high-risk investment schemes in which nearly every
Albanian family lost money.
</P>
<P>
The parliament Sunday declared a nationwide state of emergency
and then the Berisha government gave security forces orders to
shoot armed rioters on sight and imposed a dusk-to-dawn curfew
after protesters stormed a police and army weapons depot and went
on a rampage of looting and burning.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 people have been reported killed in the southern
region since last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Gjirokaster was said to be calm today after
army tanks entered the city Monday and more than 1,000 pieces of
weapons and a lot of ammunition were retaken in the southern city
of Fier, according to the state television today.
</P>
<P>
European states have expressed their grave concern over the
unrest in the nation. They fear the unrest could reignite the
Balkans by drawing in ethnic Albanians in highly sensitive
neighboring countries with unresolved ethnic and minority issues
although the civil war in the former Yugoslav region ended.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
