<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Money in Social Security Reforms in L. America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American Development
Bank (IDB) in 1996 invested 770 million U.S. dollars in social
security and pension reforms in Latin America and the Caribbean
region.
</P>
<P>
An IDB report today said the loans, which complemented
government investments, would help cover the cost of restructuring
public pension systems, and allow individuals to begin directing
social security contributions to individual saving accounts.
</P>
<P>
The total was made up of a loan of 150 million U.S. dollars to
Uruguay, a loan of 300 million U.S. dollars to Mexico, and a loan
of 320 million U.S. dollars to Argentina.
</P>
<P>
The loans represented the IDB's first direct investments in
social security reform programs, an area of increasing urgency for
policymakers in the region, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
