<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia's Trade Deficit Continues Dropping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's trade deficit
amounted to 2.2 billion U.S. dollars in 1996, decreasing by 21
percent from 2.8 billion dollars in 1995, the National
Administrative Department of Statistics says.
</P>
<P>
Exports increased to 10.574 billion dollars, up 4.4 percent
compared with 10.1 billion dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, imports decreased to 12.7 billion dollars,
1.3 percent down from 12.9 billion dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Industry was the principal destination of imports with the
majority of purchases being capital goods and construction
materials.
</P>
<P>
The largest import volumes were from the United States,
Venezuela, Japan and Germany.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, traditional exports increased by 20.4 percent in
volume and 14.4 percent in value, the most dynamic item being
coal, which increased by 42.8 percent in value and 35.5 percent in
volume.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the value of oil exports and by-products grew
32.4 percent while the volume of coffee exports rose 7.7 percent
although the value decreased 13.9 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
