<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Prepays Foreign Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Colombian government
decided to pay about 250 million U.S. dollars on its foreign debt
ahead of time to contain another drop of the dollar in the country
like the end of last year, official sources confirmed today.
</P>
<P>
The pre-payment was meant to speed up the amortizations of loans
from commercial banks which are due in the second term this year,
said Clemente de Valle, director of public credit for the Finance
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
She also announced that the public sector's foreign debt
program this year would cut 500 million dollars "to help lower
the pressure on the exchange rate and in this way, the Banco de la
Republica will not have to intervene as often in the money market
to neutralize the larger increases in the reserves due to Finance
Ministry disbursements."
</P>
<P>
This was good for the currency market as well as for the money
market, said the official.
</P>
<P>
With the decision the net flow of debt from the international
financial community will be lowered to 1.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Actually, about 1 billion dollars that Colombia received two
weeks ago from a sale of bonds have been frozen abroad. These
funds will be used to pay off loans and interest payments on the
country's foreign debt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
