<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic Briefs (Part One) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic briefs from Latin American countries:
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- The first national livestock fair in Nicaragua was
inaugurated Saturday in Managua by Nicaraguan President Arnoldo
Aleman.
</P>
<P>
The festival, which will run through March 9, was designed to
speed up the sale of Nicaraguan livestock and serve as a preview
for the agricultural exhibition of the Central American isthmus
countries in July.
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazil's state-owned Petrobras petroleum
company and Argentina's YPF petroleum company have agreed to form
a new company to explore natural gas in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
It will build a gas pipeline, approximately 400 kilometers
long, to Bahia Blanca in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The Mexican software market is estimated to
worth 1.5 billion U.S. dollars in the year 2000, representing a
sharp growth from the current 380 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Urban violence in Brazil leads to an annual loss of
one percent of its gross domestic product (GDP) or close to seven
billion dollars, according to Shahid Javed Burki, World Bank
vice-president for Latin America.
</P>
<P>
LIMA -- Foreign investments in Peru amounted to a total of 6.4
billion U.S. dollars on February 28, said the National Commission
on Foreign Investments and Technology.
</P>
<P>
In the first eight weeks of 1997, the Peruvian authorities
reported investment flows of 158.39 million dollars. 
</P>
