<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Huge Potential for U.S. Arms Sales to Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States could sell
between 3.6 and 5.2 billion U.S. dollars worth of arms to Latin
America over the next five years, a report published here today
says.
</P>
<P>
Gabriel Marcella, an analyst from the University of California,
said Latin American countries would be interested in buying
U.S. arms as their arsenals today were obsolete, dangerous to
operate and expensive to maintain.
</P>
<P>
Marcella, also an adviser to the U.S. army's Southern Command
in the Panama Canal zone, said that last May, the then Secretary
of State, Warren Christopher, and a bipartisan group of 40
U.S. senators expressed their opposition to what they called
"extraordinary restrictions on arms sales".
</P>
<P>
In 1994, U.S. arms sales in the region amounted to only three
percent of U.S exports into the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
