<HEADLINE> South China Sees Rapid Forestry Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 5 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong Province
had 13.2 billion mu (880 million hectares) of forests in 1996,
bringing the provincial coverage rate up to 55.9 percent, from
27.2 percent within a decade, and taking the lead in China.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that the overall output value of the province's
forestry industry was 19.1 billion yuan (over 2 billion US
dollars) last year, up six percent over the previous year, and
again ranking first in the country.
</P>
<P>
Shelter forest-belts are being planted on some 50 million mu of
land, affecting 70 percent of the people and area in Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
The province has set up several forestry bases each with a
major product, such as litchis, and economic returns have
attracted overseas investment, with the figure reaching nearly 100
million dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
With the progress in this area, the province has seen rapid
development in related industries. Fifty-two enterprises are in
the synthetic board business, with an output of 650,000 cubic
meters last year, one that brought in over 50 million US
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
