<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Resettling Yellow River Flood Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- China is resettling residents in
flood-prone areas on the lower reaches of the Yellow River,
China's second longest river.
</P>
<P>
Floods present a traditional dilemma for local residents --
they rebuild their houses only to see them destroyed again when
the next flood comes. Last year, two floods damaged 430,000 houses
along with roads, bridges, and telecommunication facilities.
</P>
<P>
So, Shandong Province, which straddles much of the flood-prone
region, plans to move over 280,000 people from over 580 villages
in the endangered areas within three years.
</P>
<P>
Since October of last year, Shandong has evacuated more than
160,000 people to newly-built houses farther away from the
endangered areas. Farmers who have moved to new housing have
expressed their gratitude for the government, saying that they can
start making money again, this time without the fear of a sudden
catastrophe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
