<HEADLINE> China To Resettle 20,000 People By November In Three Gorges Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, March 5 (Xinhua) -- China is scheduled to resettle
more than 20,000 local residents in the first phase from the Three
Gorges area, the world's largest hydro-electric power base, which
will be dammed this November.
</P>
<P>
The figure still only represents two percent of the total of
1.2 million people to be evacuated from the Three Gorges area by
its completion in the year 2009.
</P>
<P>
The water level is expected to rise to 82.28 meters from the
current 69 meters after the river is dammed, and is scheduled to
rise further in three more phases to a designated 175 meters.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,100 local people have already been resettled since
April of last year.
</P>
<P>
The local government is helping build more houses and furnish
employment for the would-be evacuees.  
</P>
