<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Budget Surplus Hits 340 Million Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's 1996/97 (April-March)
budget is expected to experience a surplus of 817.9 billion rupiah
(340 million U.S. dollars), Finance Minister Mar'ie Muhammad said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a hearing before the House of Representatives
Tuesday, the minister said the 1996/97 budget revenue stands at
95.840 trillion rupiah (one U.S. dollar equals 2,340 rupiah) with
expenditure expected to reach 95.022 trillion rupiah.
</P>
<P>
The budget was originally envisaged to balance at 90.6 trillion
(39.39 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Mar'ie said the higher-than-estimated revenues were due to the
realization of oil revenues estimated to be 40.7 percent higher
than budgeted.
</P>
<P>
The average price of oil until last month stood at 20.67
dollars per barrel, much higher than the 16.5 dollars per barrel
used as a basis for the budget, he said.
</P>
<P>
Other factors contributing to the higher revenue were the block
sales of share in state-owned telecommunication firm Pt. Telkom,
the conversion of funds from the non-treasury reforestation fund
and government shares in the profit of state companies.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, tax revenues and foreign assistance levels
were expected to be 0.3 percent and 11 percent lower respectively
than targeted.
</P>
<P>
Routine government spending rose 9.7 percent, while payment of
debts was at 9.7 billion dollars, 15.8 percent higher than
planned, because of the government's drive to accelerate the
repayment of high-interest foreign debt, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Total exports in 1996/97 are estimated to reach 52.6 billion
U.S. dollars. showing an increase of 10 percent from the previous
fiscal year," he said, adding that the current account deficit
will be 8.8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The minister said imports and services will be at 61.4 billion
U.S. dollars in the 1996/97 budget.
</P>
<P>
He also predicted the country's inflation will settle around an
average of 6 percent in the budget.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's inflation was 6.47 percent in calendar 1996 as
against 8.64 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said government savings are forecast to reach
23.22 trillion rupiah, up from 22.09 trillion rupiah in the
previous fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
