<HEADLINE> Manila Speeds Up Documentation of Workers in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
speed up the documentation of some 500,000 illegal Filipino
workers in eastern Malaysia in time for the six-month grace period
set by the Malaysian government before it starts a crackdown on
illegal aliens.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Foreign Affairs said Tuesday that it has
drawn a plan for the "immediate and systematic" documentation of
Filipino aliens in Malaysia, following an inter-agency meeting on
the matter, according to today's newspaper Malaya.
</P>
<P>
The departments of foreign affairs, national defense, interior
and local government and social welfare and development have
decided to put up six to nine processing centers in various areas
in eastern Malaysia to facilitate the documentation of the
Filipino workers.
</P>
<P>
Eastern Malaysia is composed of Sabah, Sarawak and Labuan,
where most of the undocumented Filipinos live and work.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the four government agencies will go to
Malaysia before March 10 to set up the processing centers.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian government has assured the Philippines it will
re-hire the Filipinos there after their stay is legalized.
</P>
</TEXT>
