<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Agrees to Join Information Technology Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has announced its
readiness to join the Information Technology Agreement (ITA) and
will scrap import tariffs on most IT products by 2000 and on the
rest by 2005, according to Krirk-krai Jirabhaet, Thai ambassador
to the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
Krirk-krai said Tuesday Thailand was able to meet the March 1
deadline for submission of its tariff reduction table, earning it
the right to participate in negotiations on product coverage and
application of non-tariff barriers to protect local industries
under the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The negotiation will last through April 1.
</P>
<P>
Krik-krai was quoted by local press as saying Thailand and
Malaysia had submitted the same conditions for joining the ITA,
with the end date for tariff cuts in 2005.
</P>
<P>
The announcement by Thailand and Malaysia brought the volume of
IT products traded among the participants to 91.3 percent of the
total world trade, only 1.3 percent higher than the minimum
requirement stated in the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The ITA was drafted by the United States, the European Union,
Canada and Japan, calling on the participants to gradually reduce
tariffs to zero by 2000. However, many developing countries
including Thailand wanted a more flexible end date for the tariff
reduction and product coverage.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was made last year at a meeting of the 18-member
Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation forum. It was later transferred
for negotiation at the WTO.
</P>
<P>
WTO representatives spent more than a month in Geneva
negotiating the timeframe before agreeing on the 2005 deadline for
tariff cuts.
</P>
<P>
By Monday, 17 countries and regions had submitted their tariff
cut tables to the WTO. The 17 that met the deadline were Thailand,
Malaysia, Macao, India. Costa Rica, Estonia, Canada, the European
Union, the United States, Japan, Hong Kong, Indonesia, Iceland,
South Korea, Norway, Switzerland and Singapore.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
