<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Apologizes to India for "Unfortunate Error" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Tuesday
apologized to India for an "unfortunate error" made by Vice
President Al Gore when he used in a letter the word "Khalistan" --
a name not recognized by Washington for India's Punjab region.
</P>
<P>
Gore used the word in a reply to a letter from Gurmit Sinngh
Aulakh, self-styled President of the Council of Khalistan based in
the U.S. capital city of Washington.
</P>
<P>
Gore's letter of February 5 went like this: "Dear Dr. Aulakh:
Thank you for writing to me regarding the ongoing civil conflict
in Khalistan...."
</P>
<P>
At a regular State Department news briefing, spokesman Nicholas
Burns said: "there was an unfortunate error in the preparation of
that letter. And I can tell you that the vice president,
obviously, supports the U.S. policy that Punjab is part of India."
</P>
<P>
The United States has "conveyed to India our regret that this
letter was sent," Burns said. "I think this is a closed matter
which we'll put behind us with the Indian government."
</P>
<P>
The embarrassing foreign policy gaffe over Khalistan has caused
an uproar in India as Gore said in the letter that Aulakh's view
"are very important to us as the president and I formulated
policies to advance the cause of peace around the world."
</P>
<P>
Aulakh, after receiving Gore's letter, said in a statement that
by acknowledging a "civil conflict in Khalistan," the United
States "recognizes the Sikh homeland Punjab as sovereign and
independent." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
