<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislators Call for Unemployment Relief Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Legislators from northeast China's
Liaoning Province, who are attending the Fifth Session of the
Eighth National People's Congress (NPC) here, today called for the
prompt formulation of a law on urban unemployment relief to assist
laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
Chen Suzhi, deputy-director of the Standing Committee of the
Liaoning Provincial People's Congress, said that the unemployment
relief law is needed not only for the smooth growth of a market
economy, but also for protecting the workers' legal rights and
interests and maintaining social stability.
</P>
<P>
As one of China's old industrial bases, Liaoning has more than
1,000 state-owned large and medium-sized enterprises above the
township level, or one tenth of the country's total. There are
approximately one million surplus workers in enterprises that are
are operating on a loss or facing serious financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, with the establishment of the market economic
structure and the deepening of reforms in state-owned enterprises,
a growing number of workers had been laid off. Some of them have
found it rather difficult to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
"Though the system of minimum life guarantee has been set up in
more than 100 cities across the country, a specific law still
needs to be formulated so as to ensure the basic living conditions
of laid-off workers," Chen noted.
</P>
<P>
The delegation of Liaoning deputies to the current NPC session
has submitted a bill asking for the law's enactment.
</P>
<P>
"With experience accumulated in the past practice of various
places, conditions are basically mature for legislation on the
issue of urban unemployment relief," said Chen.
</P>
<P>
She noted that Liaoning has formulated regulations on urban
unemployment insurance, which have been implemented across the
province and achieved remarkable results.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, Liaoning had collected 160 million yuan in
unemployment insurance premium, and paid 580 million yuan. The
province also helped 320,000 laid-off workers to find jobs again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Amends State-Owned Economic Enterprises Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has amended the State-owned
Economic Enterprises Law to pave the way for the reform and
privatization of state-owned economic enterprises (SEE).
</P>
<P>
According to the new law promulgated Tuesday by the Myanmar
State Law and Order Restoration Council, it allows state
employees' organizations to carry on the SEE with their own
investment without subscribing from state finances.
</P>
<P>
The law states these organizations have the right for perpetual
succession.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar announced in January 1995 to privatize 51 SEE in the
first phase and the process of privatization has been underway in
the form of leasing out the SEE or establishing joint ventures
with local or foreign entrepreneurs or operating either on
buy-back or counter-trade systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
