<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Provide Aid to Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA,March 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Union will provide an
emergency free economic aid of 20 million ECUs (22.90 million
U.S.dollars) beginning March to help the Bulgarian government
carry out a social relief program.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador of the European Commission to Bulgaria, Tomas
Salivan, told a press conference that about 1.40 million
Bulgarians would benefit from the aid.
</P>
<P>
Salivan said three-fourths of the money would be used to help
half a million poor Bulgarian families maintain minimum life
levels, and one-fourth would be used to buy food and medicine for
orphanages, hospitals, destitute old people's homes, disabled
centers and other social relief institutions.
</P>
<P>
The EU hoped that from its aid, a retired single man would get
2.4 ECUs (2.74 dollars) a month, a family of two retirees would get
3.6 ECUs (more than 4 dollars) and a poor family with children
under 10 years old would get 5.2 ECUs (6 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian Labor and Social Welfare Ministry said Bulgaria
was talking with the EU about the possibility of getting a loan of
60 million ECUs to help it develop its economy and overcome the
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
But Salivan said the loan would depend on negotiations between
Bulgaria and the International Funds Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
