<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Cocoa Output to Reach 400,000 Tons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's cocoa output is
projected to increase to about 400,000 tons a year by 2000 from
about 310,000 tons this year, according to the Indonesian Cocoa
Association.
</P>
<P>
The association's executive director P.S. Siswoputranto said
here Tuesday at an ASEAN Cocoa Club meeting that the positive
outlook was based on a continued increase in Indonesian cocoa
plantation acreage, sources at the meeting said today.
</P>
<P>
This year Indonesian cocoa production is expected to increase
about 5 percent to 310,000 tons from 295,000 tons last year, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The association's data show that of the 295,000 tons of cocoa
produced last year, 210,000 tons were produced by small holders,
44,000 by state plantations and 33,000 by private estates.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is now the world's third largest cocoa producer after
Ghana and the Ivory Coast. Malaysia is the region's next biggest
producer with 120,000 tons last year.
</P>
<P>
Siswoputranto said by 2000 ASEAN (Association of Southeast
Asian Nations) cocoa production was projected to increase to
500,000 tons from 464,900 tons in 1995.
</P>
<P>
About 50 representatives from the ASEAN countries are attending
the meeting which aims at identifying problems facing cocoa
production and exchanging information about the industry.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also look at the possibility of establishing a
common contract for their international trade, said the sources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
