<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Holds Export Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 5 (Xinhua) -- East China Export Fair opened
today in Shanghai, China's largest city.
</P>
<P>
The ten-day fair, now running for the sixth year, is the second
largest regional export fair in the country after the Guangzhou
Export Fair.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,500 firms from 35 provinces, municipalities and
autonomous regions are in attendance this year.
</P>
<P>
The fair, jointly sponsored by nine provinces, municipalities
and cities in East China, covers an area of 60,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
Experts expect that the trade volume at this year's fair will
increase over last year's 2.2 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The fair, experts say, has become a bridge linking the firms
in the East China provinces with their overseas counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Anhui province, for example, saw 25 percent of annual growth of
foreign trade in the eighth Five-Year-Plan period (1990-1995),
much higher than its GDP growth rate during that period.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, according to statistics, the nine sponsors of the fair
completed 23 billion US dollars of foreign trade. In 1996, the figure
increased to 100.4 billion. Their export volume now accounts for
42 percent of the nation's total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
