<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian FM Criticizes U.S. Helms-Burton Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd
Axworthy said here today that the controversial anti-Cuba
Helms-Burton law is causing a "real disruption" in the world
trading system.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy made the remarks at a press conference with United
States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. The two countries
are still locked in deep disagreement over the U.S.' anti-Cuba law
which continues to affect bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
American State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said later
the two sides had not narrowed differences over Helms-Burton.
Canada would "stick to its policy of engagement. We're going to
stick to our policy of containment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy was here to arrange a U.S. visit by the Canadian Prime
Minister, Jean Chretien, early next month.
</P>
<P>
Canada, Mexico and the European Union have been at odds with
the United States over the Cuba issue since the U.S. Congress
passed Helms-Burton last March. The law allows naturalized
Americans to sue, in U.S. courts, foreigners deemed to have
benefited from property confiscated by Cuba since 1959.
</P>
<P>
Facing strong opposition from U.S. allies, United States
President Bill Clinton has twice suspended this section of the
law. However, another section is still in effect, which allows the
U.S. to ban executives, shareholders and representatives from
investing in companies which invest in confiscated property.
</P>
<P>
The European Union took the dispute to the World Trade
Organization (WTO) last year. But last month, Washington said it
would not cooperate with the WTO investigative panel in this case.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy said the U.S. refusal to cooperate with a WTO effort
to adjudicate the disputed law "confirms my own anxiety that
Helms-Burton is causing a real disruption in the larger trading
system."
</P>
<P>
Albright dismissed the differences, saying U.S.-Canadian
relations were in excellent shape. "The strength of our
relationship is overwhelming."
</P>
<P>
"I think we made some headway in a couple of crucial areas,"
she said. "The important thing is to recognize the extent to which
we agree on the goals, which is a democracy or the movement
towards democracy in Cuba." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
