<HEADLINE> World Bank Supports Provincial Reform in Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank announced today
it will grant a loan of 125 million U.S. dollars to Brazil to help
its sub-national economic reform.
</P>
<P>
In Brazil, the sub-national public sector is made up of 26
state governments, a federal district, and 4,300 municipalities.
These provincial entities manage their financial affairs
semi-independently from the national government and account for
about half of the nation's total public expenditure.
</P>
<P>
The announcement said the loan, the first in a series of four,
would help the state of Rio Grande do Sul privatize its
telecommunications company, restructure the state power company,
Companhia Estadual de Engergia Eletrica, and support government
action to award concessions for water and sanitation, ports and
roads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
