<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Deputies Air Views on Reform of State-Owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Development of more fund sources
and establishment of a social security system will help China's
ailing state-owned enterprises overcome their difficulties.
</P>
<P>
These are among suggestions put forward by some deputies to the
National People's Congress (NPC) in session here since last
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Deputies from east China's Zhejiang, Fujian and south China's
Hainan offered their views on reform and development of
state-owned enterprises in group meetings discussing Premier Li
Peng's government work report to the NPC session.
</P>
<P>
Chen Wenxian, a deputy from Zhejiang, said lack of capital is a
main obstacle to rejuvenating state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that enterprises seek more fund sources by
introducing investment from overseas and issuing shares at home
and abroad, while improving asset management.
</P>
<P>
His opinion was concurred to by Liu Yuping, a deputy from
Fujian who is the chairman of an electronics company in Xiamen.
</P>
<P>
In his view, there is a lack of clear guidelines that banks
follow for making loan decisions. "Loan policies should be
standardized, and so should be bankruptcy proceedings," he said.
</P>
<P>
He called for vigilance against the loss of state assets
through fake bankruptcies.
</P>
<P>
Some deputies from Zhejiang and Hainan proposed that special
concern should be shown to laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
With the influx of migrant workers into cities, Deputy Wang
Yongming said, city governments should arrange an appropriate
proportion between the employment of migrant workers and
reemployment of the city laid-off.
</P>
<P>
Other deputies stressed the importance of establishing a social
security system to guarantee the basic needs of the unemployed and
alleviate the burdens of state-owned enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
