<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Extends Deadline For Surrendering Firearms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Defense Ministry today
</P>
<P>
extended the amnesty to surrender illegal firearms and
explosives till March 15 following representations by political
party leaders and other organizations, according to the ministry
sources today.
</P>
<P>
The original date to surrender firearms expired Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Search operations have been conducted countrywide jointly by
the police and the army during which 170 firearms have been seized
while about 750 have been surrendered under the amnesty, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources noted that about 3,300 more weapons have to be
returned.
</P>
<P>
They said that those in possession of unauthorized firearms
will be charged in court. Under Emergency Regulations, they are
liable to jail sentences, the death penalty and forfeiture of
property.
</P>
<P>
The hunt for firearms follows mounting political violence in
the run-up to the local government elections due on March 21.
</P>
<P>
As many as 590 incidents of election-related violence have been
reported since February 11 when government District MP Nalanda
Ellawala was killed in a clash between government supporters and
supporters of the main opposition United National Party.
</P>
<P>
The unauthorized firearms are those issued to politicians for
their protection by the United National Party during the southern
youth uprising, and not returned after the uprising was suppressed
in 1989.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that these weapons are being used in the
current spate of political violence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
