<HEADLINE> Sabotage Linked to Pakistani Train Derailment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's railway authorities
Tuesday expressed fears that Monday's train derailment may have
been deliberately caused, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
Eleven railway employees have been suspended in connection with
the train accident which happened early Monday in central
Pakistan, leaving 127 people dead and hundreds injured.
</P>
<P>
The train driver and fireman, who escaped the tragedy unhurt,
have been taken into custody, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The other nine workers including the train guard and examiner
have also been suspended.
</P>
<P>
An inquiry report is expected today to be submitted to
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
Five cars of the train, which was heading for Pakistan's
southern port city of Karachi, skidded off the tracks early Monday
morning outside the rural station of Mirshah near Khanewal,
northeast of Multan in Punjab province.
</P>
<P>
Passengers were enjoying sound sleep when the train derailed,
which could be one of the reasons for the high death toll.
</P>
<P>
The actual cause of the accident has not been determined so
far, but some reports suggested that some problem in the brake
system of the train may have directly led to the derailment.
</P>
<P>
The train reportedly developed some problem in the brake system
just before approaching the Mirshah Station, which made the driver
unable to stop the train, sources at the Khanewal Station were
quoted as saying.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
