<HEADLINE> Grenade Blast Not Linked to Sri Lankan Tamil Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan police have ruled out
the possibility of Sunday's grenade blast in the hill capital of
Nuwara Eliya near Queens Cottage, the official residence of
President Chandrika Kumaratunga, as being the work of Tamil
rebels.
</P>
<P>
The explosion occurred three kilometers from the venue where
the ruling party was due to hold an election meeting and half a
kilometer from the president's Queens Cottage in Nuwara Eliya.
</P>
<P>
The president who later addressed the meeting was at Queens
Cottage at the time of the explosion.
</P>
<P>
Police sources today said that a student who died during the
explosion had found a hand grenade in a shrub jungle nearby ten
days earlier and had hidden it at another location.
</P>
<P>
On the fateful day, he pulled out the grenade to show it to a
friend when it exploded, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
His friend was also injured in the explosion. He has been
detained for questioning. Police have also detained the parents
and sister of the dead student for questioning.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, police thought that Tamil rebels could have been
behind the incident, the sources added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
