<HEADLINE> U.S. Calls For Refugee Corridors in Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Tuesday
called on Zairian rebel leader Laurent Kabila to open corridors
from Zaire to Rwanda so that Rwandan refugees can return to their
homeland.
</P>
<P>
"We are formally calling today for Mr Laurent Kabila to allow
the opening of these corridors so that innocent people can flee
the fighting," Nicholas Burns of the State Department told a
briefing.
</P>
<P>
There were over a million Rwandan Hutu refugees in eastern
Zaire, who fled their homes after the civil war in Rwanda in
1994. Last December, a great portion of the refugees made their
way back to Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
However, there are still more than 200,000 refugees scattered
in eastern Zaire and unable to return home because of fighting
between the Zairian government troops and Tutsi-led rebels.
</P>
<P>
Burns said State Department refugee coordinator Phyllis Oakley
discussed the situation on Tuesday by telephone with Emma Bonino,
the European Union's humanitarian affairs commissioner. They
agreed the corridors should be opened in order to "contribute
humanitarian assistance to these refugees." 
</P>
</TEXT>
