<HEADLINE> Nepal's National Airline Urged to Improve Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has urged
Royal Nepal Airlines (RNA), the country's national flag carrier,
to improve its management for reversing its loss-making
performance, a senior cabinet member said today.
</P>
<P>
A cabinet meeting last month gave three options to the
airline's management with a view to making the RNA able to compete
under free-market conditions with the participation of private
sector, Finance Minister Ram Sharan Mahat was quoted by the
Kathmandu Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the options include giving away the RNA's
management to private sector under contract basis, privatization
and setting up a joint venture with a foreign air carrier.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said that his ministry will not support a
deal of two wide-bodied jets for the RNA, proposed by the European
aircraft maker Airbus Industrie, due to the depressing performance
of the airline.
</P>
<P>
The Airbus consortium recently proposed a 200 million U.S.
dollar deal to the RNA for two A-330 jets on a hire-purchase basis
with 60 million dollars of down payment.
</P>
<P>
Under the Airbus proposal, the remaining 140 million dollars
for the deal would be paid with soft credits from Airbus
consortium partner countries after the Nepali government provides
the down payment or necessary guarantees.
</P>
<P>
The government "can't keep on pouring money into the RNA when
it continues adding on losses", the finance minister said.
</P>
<P>
The two A-330s, if hire-purchased, would fly on the airline's
European routes, which have made heavy losses during recent years,
according to airline sources.
</P>
<P>
The latest financial report of the RNA's European operation
showed a net loss of 21.6 million dollars for the period of nearly
two years ending in March 1995, they said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
