<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Balanced-Budget Amendment Defeated in US Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- In a major setback for
Republicans in the U.S. Congress, the balanced-budget amendment to
the U.S. Constitution was defeated today in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
The vote, 66-34, was one shy of the two-thirds needed to
approve a constitutional amendment in the country.
</P>
<P>
It also marked the third year in a row that the Republicans had
failed to muster the support to pass a cornerstone of their
conservative agenda.
</P>
<P>
The proposed amendment would require a balanced budget by 2002
and every year thereafter, unless the House of Representatives and
the Senate vote otherwise. Exceptions could be made in cases of
war or other military conflict.
</P>
<P>
But Democrats had long since made up their minds to defeat it.
They said the amendment would endanger the Social Security system
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Senate Democratic leader Tom Daschle said today, "A
balanced-budget amendment shouldn't force us to break that
historic contract."
</P>
<P>
Passage by a two-thirds majority was needed to send the measure
to the House, where the amendment has stalled. Approval there
would submit it to the states for ratification.
</P>
<P>
The Republicans have sought its approval for years, and made
it a cornerstone of their major objectives when they took control
of Congress two years ago.
</P>
<P>
A similar amendment cleared the House in 1995 but defeated with
a vote of 66-34. The second vote also failed with a 64-34 vote in
June of 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
