<HEADLINE> Match-fixing Trial Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The biggest match-fixing trial in
England in 30 years ended on Tuesday after the jury failed to
reach a verdict.
</P>
<P>
Former Liverpool goalkeeper Bruce Grobbelaar, his Wimbledon
counterpart Hans Segers, former Aston Villa forward John Fashanu
and Malaysian businessman Heng Suan Lim were charged of
match-fixing. But they all pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
If they were convicted, they would have faced sentences of up
to seven years in jail and unlimited fines.
</P>
<P>
Prosecuting counsel David Calvert-Smith said the crown wanted a
retrial but said the decision would have to be taken "at the
highest level".
</P>
<P>
Calvert-Smith said the decision could be made later this week.
</P>
