<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Appeals for Int'l Assistance to Earthquake Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian government today
formally appealed to the international community for humanitarian
assistance after strong earthquakes killed 965 people and injured
2,600 others.
</P>
<P>
As of today, apart from the casualties, more than 60,000 people
have been affected, 20 villages have been completely destroyed and
another 80 villages have been 40 percent to 90 percent destroyed
by two major earthquakes and more than 133 aftershocks in late
February and early March, according to the United Nations
Department of Humanitarian Affairs (DHA) based in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
The affected province of Ardebil, 420 kilometers northwest of
Teheran, has a population of more than 1 million living in 2,000
villages. The temperature there at present is down to minus 10
degrees celsius and some areas are covered by snow of up to 1.5
meters. There is heavy damage to roads, electrical power lines,
water supplies, telecommunications and transport networks. Many
schools, rural health centers and public buildings have also
suffered severe damage.
</P>
<P>
The preferred assistance will be cash contributions or material
contributions including the following items:
</P>
<P>
-- Food: rice, grains, sugar, cooking oil, canned food and tea;
</P>
<P>
-- Shelter: tents, family tents, blankets, plastic sheeting,
cookers, floor cover of 12 square meters, kitchen sets, lanterns,
water buckets and shoes;
</P>
<P>
-- Medical supplies: essential drugs, in-patient drugs,
dressing supplies, nursing care supplies, operation theater
supplies, vaccines, x-ray machines and supplies;
</P>
<P>
-- Water and sanitation: water pumps, water tanks, water
distribution points, disinfectants, pesticides, chlorinometer,
sprayers, fiberglass latrines, prefabricated bathrooms, chlorine
powder;
</P>
<P>
-- Others: tractors, combines, deep cultivators, agricultural
equipment and attachment, wheat seeds, barley seeds, potato seeds,
etc.
</P>
<P>
International organizations and several governments have
contributed 565,000 U.S. dollars in cash and material to date,
according to the DHA. It has been agreed that, after the relief
operation, a joint government and UN team will evaluate the use of
the relief assistance and provide a detailed report to the donor
community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
