<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Dollar Grows Stronger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar hit a three-year
high against the mark today, rallying mainly on strong U.S.
economic data, new hints of enlarged German unemployment and more
uncertainty over Europe's launching of single currency.
</P>
<P>
The dollar reached an intraday high of 1.7152 marks, the
strongest since April 1994, before settling in New York at 1.7146
marks, up from 1.6980 Monday and up 13 percent so far for the year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the U.S. dollar will grow stronger, especially
against the mark, based on the likelihood that interest rates will
rise in the United States but remain static or fall in Germany,
which is suffering from a lackluster economy.
</P>
<P>
The dollar settled at its high for the day at 122.16 yen,
up from 121.27 yen Monday and its first close above 122 yen in six
days. For the year, the dollar is up 5.4 percent against the yen.
</P>
<P>
The pound cost 1.6126 dollars, down from 1.6176 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Demand for the dollar increased on new reports showing
unexpectedly strong housing sales in the U.S. in January and a
surprising surge in the Leading Economic Indicators, the main
forecasting gauge prepared by the Conference Board.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also derived strength from a leaked report that the
number of unemployed German workers hit another postwar high in
February, with 4.671 million people jobless.
</P>
<P>
U.S. February employment data, due Friday, are expected to be
strong.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also grew stronger against other major currencies,
except for the Canadian dollar, in New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
