<HEADLINE> US Decides Not to Cut Off Aid to Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States said today
that it will not cut off its aid to Albania despite of latest
developments in the country.
</P>
<P>
"This would not be in the self-interests of the United
States," U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told
reporters when referring to suggestions that the U.S. cut off
its aid to Albania.
</P>
<P>
"We have a 27 million U.S. dollar assistance program to
Albania in fiscal year 1997," he said, claiming that all of the
money is directed to building a "democracy" in Albania.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. spokesman expressed deep concern about the
situation in Albania.
</P>
<P>
"We regret very much that the Albanian authorities are using
the state of emergency to intimidate opposition politicians... to
shut down Voice of America," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Western allies are coordinating their
positions on the issue.
</P>
<P>
"We are working very closely with the Italian government and
with the Greek government... to see if there can be some unified
position... to make sure that we're speaking to the Albanian
government, all of us in the West, with one voice," he affirmed.
</P>
