<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Army Lowers Recruit Standard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Army said today it has
lowered the recruit standard and begun to recruit people who have
not finished high school, as the recruit was hurt by sexual
harassment allegations in the Army and the controversy over a
mysterious Gulf War illness.
</P>
<P>
Publicity about a rash of sexual harassment allegations in the
Army, combined with controversy over a mysterious Gulf War illness
syndrome, has hurt recruiting, Lt. Gen. Frederick Vollrath, the
Army's chief personnel officer said.
</P>
<P>
Besides lowering the standard, Vollrath said, the Army is
offering a range of new financial and other incentives to attract
recruits.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary William Cohen, when testifying before
Congress last week, blamed the drop-off in recruit quality on
negative publicity.
</P>
<P>
"Every time you have a bad headline, it impacts recruiting,"
Cohen said. "If we can eliminate those headlines, we can solve the
problem in recruiting."
</P>
<P>
Preliminary figures for the first four months of the 1997
budget year (October 1996-January 1997) show the Army has scored
lowest among the services on two of the three major yardsticks by
which recruit quality is measured, an Associated Press report
said.
</P>
<P>
In that four-month period, 90 percent of the Army's recruits
were holders of high school diplomas, compared with 91 percent for
the Navy, 94 percent for the Marines and 99 percent for the Air
Force.
</P>
<P>
The Army has lowered the recruit standard from having no fewer
than 95 percent high school graduates to 90 percent, which is the
minimum required by the Defense Department for all services.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Army needs to recruit more than two years ago
because of higher drop-offs. Though the Army is not growing in
overall numbers, it needs 89,700 inductees this year, up from
63,000 two years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Manufacturers Criticize Unilateral Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. manufacturers today
criticized the government policy of unilateral economic sanctions
against U.S. companies trading with some countries, saying that it
only costs thousands of American jobs.
</P>
<P>
Unveiling a major new study on the scope and impact of
unilateral sanctions on U.S. companies, President of the U.S.
National Association of Manufacturers Jerry Jasinowski said the
U.S. sanctions are a massive patchwork "with bad results."
</P>
<P>
"Unilateral sanctions are little more than postage stamps we
use to send messages to other countries at the cost of thousands
of American jobs," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "It is difficult to argue that any of the 61 measures
authorized over the past four years have changed the behavior of
the 35 targeted countries."
</P>
<P>
Tracy O'Rourke, CEO and Chairman of Varian Associates Inc, said
that the U.S. government policy of unilateral sanctions "simply
don't work."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press luncheon today, he said that cutting off
American trade and investment in a so-called rogue state "is
sure-fire way to diminish American influence there."
</P>
<P>
"If we are serious about competing in the globe marketplace, we
need to be seen a reliable trading partner," he said.
</P>
<P>
The new study unveiled today was titled "A Catalog of New U.S.
Unilateral Economic Sanctions for Foreign Policy Purposes
1993-1996."
</P>
<P>
It showed that 61 U.S. laws and executive actions were enacted
to authorize unilateral economic sanctions for U.S. foreign policy
purposes in the four-year period of 1993-1996.
</P>
<P>
The sanctioned countries represent 2.3 billion potential
consumers of U.S. goods and services and the export markets
worthing 790 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
