<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: US Ready to Deploy New Nuclear Bomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States is ready to
deploy a bunker-busting nuclear bomb that could strike targets
hundreds of meters below the ground, the Defense News weekly
reported in its latest edition.
</P>
<P>
The bomb, called B61-11, was designed to replace the B53 bomb,
which nuclear war planners use to target deeply buried Russian
command and control facilities.
</P>
<P>
The B61-11, which was completed in development in December,
directs the bulk of its energy downward, destroying everything
buried beneath it to depth of 700 meters, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Prior to its development, the best U.S. earth-penetrating
nuclear weapon was the B53, a nine megaton bomb with a force equal
to 9 million tons of TNT, penetrates the earth by creating a
massive crater, rather than the more precise blow the B61-11 is
meant to deliver.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the B53 cannot be carried by the B-2 bomber, and
offers less assurance that it will destroy its target than does
the B61-11, arms experts said.
</P>
<P>
The B61-11 not only can be carried by the B-2, but also can
produce explosions ranging from 300 tons of TNT to more than
300,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
It was the first new bomb developed by the Department of Energy
since the end of the Cold War. Independent arms control advocates
warned that the B61-11 could undermine U.S. efforts to reduce
tensions with Russia.
</P>
<P>
Bill Arkin, an arms control consultant, was quoted as saying
that developing a bomb to destroy buried Russian command and
control facilities could be destabilizing.
</P>
<P>
"What that signals to the Russians is far more detrimental than
any gains it makes in deterrence," Arkin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970305.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Proposes Rome Style for Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat suggested today that the final settlement of the issue of
Jerusalem's status could copy the style of Rome, making the Holy
City to be the twin capitals for Israel and Palestine.
</P>
<P>
"We have a very important example -- Rome. Rome is the capital
of the Vatican, and it is at the same time the capital of the
Italian government," Arafat told reporters at a news conference at
the National Press Club, Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
"Why not we can repeat the same, capital of two states, the
state of Palestine and Israel? If there is a will, there is a
way," he added.
</P>
<P>
East Jerusalem is the traditionally Arab residential area,
which was captured by Israel during the 1967 Middle East war.
Israel has ever since claimed the city as an undivided entity and
declared that it would be its capital, defying U.N. Security
Council resolutions 252 and 465, which condemned completely the
annexation of the Holy City.
</P>
<P>
Its plan approved last Wednesday by the Israeli government to
build Jewish housing in east Jerusalem has drawn worldwide
criticisms, which called it a violation of the U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said Monday before his talks with U.S. President Bill
Clinton at the White House that Israel's housing project was aimed
"to squeeze and to isolate Jerusalem," which would surely
"torpedo" the peace process in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
He kept on with his condemnations of Israel at today's news
conference, saying, "The last decision to build a new settlement
in Abu Ghehaim Mountain (east Jerusalem) is a real challenge to
the peace process because it will isolate Jerusalem more and more
and more and more, and to separate between Jerusalem and
Bethlehem."
</P>
<P>
He, however, told reporters at the National Press Club that he
would continue to take hard job in pursuing the final peace in the
volatile region.
</P>
<P>
"We have to work hard now to carry on with this very difficult
job," he said. "We have no other alternative. And in spite of the
difficulties, which we are taking, we have one alternative: to
carry on with the peace process."
</P>
<P>
He said he had "very constructive, positive, warm talks" with
Clinton, who gave the Palestinians support by denouncing Israel's
housing project as "building mistrust" between the Israelis and
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"I can't say and I haven't the right to say what he (Clinton)
is going to do, but I am sure he will push forward with all his
capability, with all his capacity, to save the peace process,"
Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
At a State Department regular briefing today, spokesman
Nicholas Burns said the United States was very "disappointed" at
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's intention to go ahead
with the housing project in east Jerusalem withing a couple of
weeks.
</P>
<P>
"We wish this decision had not been taken. There's been an
erosion of trust and confidence. What we need to do right now is
try to build that back up between the Palestinians and the
Israelis," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
