<HEADLINE> Renault's Layoff Plan Meets With Strong Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The plan to lay off 3,100 workers in
Belgium and 2,764 workers in France by the automaker Renault has
met with strong opposition from France's rightwing as well as
leftwing political parties.
</P>
<P>
French unionists said today that Renault plans to lay off 2,764
workers in its assembly plants and managing offices in France in
1997, after it announced that it will close its Vilvoorde plant
near Brussels where 3,100 workers are employed.
</P>
<P>
While Belgium remains under a state of shock and fury over
Renault's decision, French unions and leftist parties have
expressed solidarity with the Belgians and called for the
scrapping of the plan.
</P>
<P>
First Secretary of the French Socialist Party Lionel Jospin
today asked the French government to intervene to stop Renault's
plan to close the Vilvoorde plant and cut its work force in
France.
</P>
<P>
He said that the "brutal plan" to close Vilvoorde is
"financially, industrially and socially aberrant."
</P>
<P>
The president of the Communist Party group in the French
Senate, Helene Luc, has called for a parliamentary debate over
Renault's decision and re-nationalization of Renault, which now
remains half state-owned and half private.
</P>
<P>
The president of the ruling RPR group in the National Assembly,
Michel Pericard, said that there was no reason for Renault to make
things "so brutal," while other rightwing parliamentarians also
called it brutality.
</P>
<P>
Renault reported a 5 billion franc (1 billion U.S. dollar) loss
in 1996, due to globalization of the auto market and fierce
competition from other European automakers. But French unions
estimate the deficit at 6 billion francs (1.2 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The decision by Renault came at a moment when unemployment
stands at 12.7 percent in France and more than 13 percent in
Belgium, while the average unemployment rate in Europe stands
close to the post-war highs of 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
It also came when Europe is worried that globalization of the
world economy will cause more and more European companies to shift
jobs to countries with cheaper labor costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
