<HEADLINE> Toronto Residents Vote Against Mega-City Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The majority of residents in
Toronto and its five municipalities have voted against a mega-city
plan by the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
Results in a plebiscite show 73 percent of Toronto city
residents and an average of 78 percent people in the five
municipalities said NO to the proposed amalgamation, said local
media reports.
</P>
<P>
Despite today's results, the Ontario provincial government said
it will go ahead with the merger, though a couple of changes might
be made to its original plan.
</P>
<P>
Merger opponents say that combining Canada's largest city and
its five neighbors into one mega-city of 2.4 million people would
impair democracy, destroy neighborhood, raise taxes and cause a
lot of other ills.
</P>
<P>
But the government argued that the merger would eliminate
duplication of services, cut costs and raise efficiency in
particular.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the province, some 350 municipalities are reported
to be considering merging with their neighboring communities.
</P>
</TEXT>
