<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Otis Elevator Expands Asian Share in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jean-Pierre van Rooy, company president, said that Otis
performed well, in Asia in particular, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"We're confident about the future (in the Asian market)," van
Rooy said, "because accelerated urbanization throughout Asia will
continue to increase demand for our products."
</P>
<P>
The president, who will become chairman of the company on April
1, also said that in Asia China is a very promising market, in
which Otis has already set up four joint ventures in Tianjin,
Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou, respectively.
</P>
<P>
From 1990 to 1996, the company's compound annual growth rate in
China exceeded 40 percent, faster than any other region in the
world. Its sales last year reached 300 million U.S. dollars, 20
percent more than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Today, he said, Otis revenues in the Pacific Asia account for
1.6 billion U.S. dollars or nearly 30 percent of the company's
annual revenues.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the secret of its success, van Rooy said that the
company invested 100 million U.S. dollars in product innovation
last year.
</P>
<P>
In July 1996, it announced the release of Odyssey, the world's
first elevator which incorporates horizontal and vertical movement
and can stretch up to 1,000 meters. However, the company is still
looking for a buyer, primarily in Pacific Asia, which has had a
construction boom for the past decade.
</P>
<P>
The company president also listed decentralized management and
strong partnership with local companies as their way to success.
</P>
<P>
Now its products are found in the Ocean Park in Hong Kong,
Eiffel Tower in Paris and Petronas Twin-Towers in Kuala Lumpur,
Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
