<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO -- Gambia will import all its medicines, chemicals and
medical supplies from Egypt under an agreement between the two
sides, the Egyptian MENA news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Contacts are underway to determine Gambia's actual needs of
those products so that exports may begin later this month, head
of the Egyptian Pharmaceutical Holding Company said today.
</P>
<P>
The company is also studying prospects of exporting medicines
to Gambia's neighbors, he added.
</P>
<P>
The two countries agreed that Gambia would import all its
medicines, chemicals and medical supplies from Egypt when Gambian
President Yaya Jameh visited here last month.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- After the conclusion of the Hebron Agreement
between Israel and the Palestinians in January, signs are
pointing to a recovery of the tourism in this country, Israel
Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Avraham Rosental, director-general of the
Israeli Hotel Association, as saying that reservations in local
hotels have been up since the implementation of the Hebron
Agreement.
</P>
<P>
Rosental said that after six months of decline in the number
of tourists coming to Israel, tourist operators are suggesting
that the recovery they have been waiting for has finally started.
</P>
<P>
Israel's tourism industry suffered a huge set back in 1996,
due to series of suicide bombing attacks in February and March
and a serious armed confrontation between Israeli soldiers and
Palestinian police in September.
</P>
<P>
Rosental said that the Israeli government and private tourist
operators, as well as the Hotel Association, are carrying out
market promotions in Europe and the United States to attract
tourists.
</P>
<P>
He said that Israel and together with the whole Middle East
is a very attractive market for visitors, but, "only a right
peaceful environment will bring more tourists to an area."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
